<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Feb. 21, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Talks Start Up Again  
</P>
<P>
	RAMBOUILLET, France (AP) -- Kosovo peace talks are expected to  
start up again today after yesterday's decision to extend the 
deadline for an accord to Tuesday. NATO had threatened airstrikes 
against the Serbs if they did not reach an agreement with Albanian 
insurgents by noon yesterday, but the United States and five other 
nations allowed the dialogue to continue. Despite the extension, 
preparations for NATO action will continue until the negotiating 
parties accept all provisions for autonomy for ethnic Albanians, 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said. 

</P>
<P>
	Finance Leaders Fight Global Crisis  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Finance officials from the world's richest  
nations met yesterday in Bonn to try to find ways to prevent the 
spread of the global economic crisis. Germany, the host of today's 
meeting of finance officials from the seven leading industrialized 
nations, was pushing an ambitious campaign to regulate exchange 
rates. The idea is staunchly opposed by the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	'Shakespeare In Love' Script Honored  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The authors of the romantic comedy  
``Shakespeare In Love'' beat the writers of the harrowing war drama 
``Saving Private Ryan'' to win the Writers Guild of America award 
for original screenplay. Marc Norman and Tom Stoppard shared the 
award for ``Shakespeare,'' which bested ``Bulworth,'' with 
screenplay by Warren Beatty and Jeremy Pikser; ``Saving Private 
Ryan,'' by Robert Rodat; ``The Truman Show,'' by Andrew Niccol; and 
``The Opposite of Sex,'' by Don Roos. The guild's 51st annual 
awards were announced yesterday in ceremonies held in Beverly Hills 
and New York. 

</P>
<P>
	Talks Fail To Stop Africa Fighting  
</P>
<P>
	ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) -- A European Union delegation has failed to  
broker a ceasefire between Eritrea and Ethiopia after meeting with 
the leaders of both countries on the Horn of Africa, the leader of 
the team said yesterday. Representatives from Germany, Austria, 
Finland and the European Commission met yesterday with Eritrean 
President Isaias Afwerki following talks Friday with Ethiopia's 
foreign minister in his country's capital, Addis Ababa. Both 
countries blame the other for instigating the renewed fighting at 
four fronts along their disputed common border, which erupted Feb. 
6 following an eight month stalemate. 

</P>
<P>
	eBay Halts Online Sales of Guns  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Concerned about its ability to comply  
with firearms laws, Internet auction company eBay says it will no 
longer allow the sale of guns or ammunition. The said Friday that 
firearms sales was an area of growing concern because online 
sellers cannot guarantee that buyers meet all the qualifications. 
Certain guns and ammunition are illegal to sell in some states, and 
federal laws govern many aspects of firearms purchases, including 
how weapons can be shipped and who may purchase them. 

</P>
<P>
	London Police Accused of Racism  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- London's police force was riven by institutional  
racism that was a key factor in its failure to thoroughly 
investigate the slaying six years ago of a black teen-ager, a 
newspaper quoted a government report as saying. The Sunday 
Telegraph published excerpts of the report on the death of 
18-year-old Stephen Lawrence, who was stabbed to death in 1993. The 
inquiry, ordered in July 1997, has raised serious questions of 
police incompetence and highlighted racial antagonism in some 
rundown London districts. The Metropolitan Police have acknowledged 
they failed to investigate properly and apologized. 

</P>
<P>
	Pacers Edge Bucks 82-80  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Chris Mullin blocked Vinny Del Negro's layup,  
then swished a 20-foot jumper with 18.3 seconds remaining to lift 
the Indiana Pacers to an 82-80 victory over the Milwaukee Bucks on 
last night. Glenn Robinson, who scored 31 points for the Bucks, had 
his shot blocked by Antonio Davis with eight seconds left. Reggie 
Miller scored 20 points for the Pacers. Dale Davis added 10 points 
for Indiana. Mullin had nine. 

</P>
<P>
	Tryba Takes Nissan Golf Lead  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ted Tryba, continuing this year's  
record-setting run of low scores, shot a 10-under-par 61 yesterday 
to rewrite the Riviera Country Club record and vault into the 
Nissan Open lead. Tryba, who bogeyed the final hole by muffing his 
chip from the fringe and missing a 12-foot par putt, had nine 
birdies to go with an eagle on No. 11, where he sank a 30-foot 
putt. His record round put him at 13-under 200, two shots in front 
of a most imposing trio: Tiger Woods, Ernie Els and Davis Love III. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
