<HEADLINE> More Delays for NASA Space Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Two months after launching the  
foundation of its new space station, NASA isn't sure how many more 
flights -- or how many more years -- will be needed to finish the 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, NASA's biggest partner is to blame.  
</P>
<P>
	The Russian Space Agency has fallen behind yet again on its main  
contribution, a control module that's meant to double as the crew 
quarters. The upshot is more delays and rising costs for the 
international space station. 
</P>
<P>
	Except for a supply trip by shuttle Discovery this May, all  
assembly missions are on hold until the Russians launch the control 
module, the crucial third piece of the space station. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will launch. It's just a matter of when,'' says Frank  
Culbertson, NASA's deputy program manager for space station 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's so-called service module should have soared in April  
1998, then in December 1998, then in April 1999, then in July 1999. 
Now an engineering evaluation by NASA shows that despite $60 
million in U.S. assistance, the 43-foot compartment won't be ready 
to fly before September. 
</P>
<P>
	And it may not be ready before November.  
</P>
<P>
	Russia's economic crisis is to blame for the 1 1/2-year holdup --  
the Russian government simply is not providing enough money -- 
although computer software problems have emerged in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian space officials expect to more or less complete the  
service module next month and ship it from Moscow to the launch 
site in Kazakstan. Engineers typically need 4 1/2 months to eight 
months at the launch site, however, to prepare a space station 
component for flight, says Culbertson. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight months of work would bump the launch of the service module  
to November. And that would bump everything else, including the 
arrival of the first permanent crew, penciled in for early next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Culbertson says that while some Russian space officials are  
embarrassed about the situation, ``most of them are fairly 
pragmatic -- they've dealt with this before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They know the schedule pressure that we are under from  
Congress and the need to keep things moving because it costs money 
when you delay,'' he says. ``But they also are not going to ship it 
before it's ready. They've been very clear about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's about the only clear message lately from Russia.  
</P>
<P>
	When NASA revealed last month that the service module would fly  
no earlier than September, two months later than promised, the 
Russian Space Agency's PR office promptly issued a denial. 
</P>
<P>
	Days passed before Russian officials publicly acknowledged the  
delay. 
</P>
<P>
	Around the same time, word came from Moscow that if benefactors  
could be found, the antiquated Mir would remain in orbit another 
three years rather than face a fatal plunge this summer to free up 
money for the international space station. A deal was close, 
officials insisted. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, the head of the Russian Space Agency, Yuri  
Koptev, said the mystery investors had backed off. Explained 
Koptev: ``It was just wishful thinking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NASA Administrator Daniel Goldin says Russia can expect ``zero  
dollars'' from the United States to fulfill its share of the 
international space station. At one point last year, an exasperated 
NASA considered paying the Russians as much as $600 million to keep 
them in the 16-nation project. 
</P>
<P>
	``It disincentives the Russian government to fund the Russian  
Space Agency,'' Goldin told reporters at a Feb. 1 budget briefing. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, to cover anticipated Russian shortfalls, NASA proposes  
to spend an additional $2 billion on the international space 
station over the next five years. About $1.2 billion would come 
from within NASA, the result of canceled or shuffled programs; the 
Clinton administration would provide the remaining $800 million. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA managers hope to have a better grasp of the service module  
problems -- and the domino impact on space station assembly -- after 
meeting with their Russian counterparts this week in Moscow. 
Another meeting is planned for late March. 
</P>
<P>
	James Oberg, an expert in Russian space affairs, says NASA  
should not expect instant and simple answers. The Russians 
genuinely do not know when the service module will be ready to fly 
because ``it's uncharted territory -- they're trying to operate with 
a skeleton staff and an aging cadre.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you can rule out September of this year or  
September of next year,'' says Oberg. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, NASA is sticking to its projected 2004 completion date  
for the international space station -- ``if we're able to keep to 
this schedule,'' Culbertson cautions. It's also sticking to 45 
assembly flights, although Culbertson notes: ``I wouldn't put money 
on that number, either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cost of the finished product? Estimates vary. Some $60  
billion, counting launches, is as good a figure as any. 
</P>
<P>
	Delays and costs will continue to mount if NASA gives up on  
Russia's service module and launches a substitute. 
</P>
<P>
	Without Russia's service module or a U.S. fill-in, the first two  
pieces of the space station would have to be junked. Shuttle 
astronauts painstakingly linked the Russian Zarya and U.S. Unity 
modules in December following a one-year, Russian-prompted delay. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA has until April 2000 to get a control module -- any control  
module -- up. That's when the electronics on the two-piece space 
station will no longer be able to handle the load alone, causing 
the outpost to tumble out of control. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a long way off,'' says Culbertson.  
</P>
<P>
	Maybe so, but the clock is ticking.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
