<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American, Attendants Continue Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Negotiations between American Airlines and its  
flight attendants are going relatively smoothly, to the point where 
the company says it will pay for flights canceled during the recent 
pilot sickout -- a sharp contrast to the company's relationship with 
its pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 600,000 passengers were stranded when the thousands of  
pilots called in sick to protest pilot pay issues resulting from 
AMR Corp.'s recent purchase of smaller, low-cost carrier Reno Air. 
The 10-day job action, which resulted in more than 6,600 canceled 
flights, ended last week after a federal judge held the Allied 
Pilots Association in contempt. 
</P>
<P>
	Flight attendants, and pilots, who showed up at the gate during  
the company dispute could have lost out financially since they 
normally do not receive flight pay when a plane doesn't take off. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision Friday by AMR, parent company of American, to pay  
flight crews for scheduled flights scrubbed during the labor rift 
is expected to go a long way during negotiations with both union 
groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is unprecedented and goes beyond the contract. We were  
very, very pleased,'' said Cliff O'Neal, spokesman for the 
Association of Professional Flight Attendants. 
</P>
<P>
	Company spokesman John Hotard said the company wanted to pay the  
people who came to work since pilots who did not show up would get 
sick pay. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did it to protect all of the work groups. We did it for  
pilots and flight attendants who stepped up to the line ready to 
fly,'' said Hotard. 
</P>
<P>
	The leadership for APFA, which represents nearly 20,000 members,  
told flight attendants during the dispute that they could not 
become involved in the pilots' problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot and will not interfere in this dispute,'' union  
president Denise Hedges told flight attendants. ``As painful as 
this is, it is out of our control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hedges said that the faltering of pilot talks over Reno Air  
doesn't really effect the flight attendants contract. 
</P>
<P>
	She said flight attendants from both airlines will be merged  
based on seniority. The method will be voted on at an APFA 
convention in March. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not expect any serious difficulty in this matter,'' said  
Ms. Hedges. 
</P>
<P>
	American Airlines' flight attendants have been in contract  
negotiations with the company since September and some tentative 
agreements have been reached. 
</P>
<P>
	The issues remaining on the table for the APFA are primarily pay  
and improvements in retirement benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hedges says she's optimistic that the union will be able to  
reach an agreement without a repeat of the contentious round of 
bargaining in 1993 that eventually resulted in a strike. After most 
flights for the airline were grounded for five days, President 
Clinton intervened and forced the company back to the bargaining 
table to settle the dispute through binding arbitration. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this atmosphere, we have a real opportunity for positive,  
productive collective bargaining between the company and our 
union,'' Ms. Hedges said. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
