<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leafs Not Quite At Home Yet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- The ice was choppy, the fans subdued. Even with  
an overtime victory to inaugurate their new arena, the Maple Leafs 
had a tough time adjusting to the departure from Maple Leaf 
Gardens. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's that way for the fans, too,'' Leafs president Ken Dryden  
said. ``There is so much to take in, so much new to see, that you 
find yourself looking at other things, not just the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rough ice contributed to sloppy play throughout the Leafs'  
3-2 win Saturday night over Montreal to open the Air Canada Centre. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a tight game against an arch-rival, the crowd was  
passive for long stretches, rarely erupting into the ``Go Leafs, 
Go!'' chant that was a staple at the smaller, 68-year-old Gardens. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was quiet,'' Leafs forward Derek King said. ``This  
certainly wasn't your average Toronto-Montreal game. It felt like I 
was in a strange place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Leafs had lost 6-2 to Chicago a week earlier in the  
ballyhooed farewell game at the Gardens, and they again had to cope 
with hype Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is such a self-conscious game,'' Dryden said. ``You want it  
to go so right and you play like that, but it doesn't have the 
unconscious energy you need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from the ice, there was little criticism from players or  
fans about the spaciousness and amenities at the 18,800-seat Air 
Canada Centre. From the state-of-the-art scoreboard video screens 
to the padded seats to the plush dressing rooms, it made the 
cramped, aging Gardens seem like a relic. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the players missed the raucous bellows of the Gardens crowd.  
They also noticed that many of high-cost seats close to the ice at 
the new arena remained empty for several minutes at the start of 
the second and third periods, while those fans lingered in VIP 
lounges. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took awhile for fans to filter into their seats and it took  
away from the atmosphere,'' winger Steve Thomas said. ``I guess 
they were downstairs having a beer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas scored the winning goal with 72 seconds left in overtime  
on a precise cross-ice pass from rookie Ladislav Kohn. It was one 
of only 24 shots taken by the Leafs during the game as the choppy 
ice disrupted the passing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to be able to pass the puck stick-to-stick,'' Toronto  
coach Pat Quinn said. ``We don't want to bang it off the glass or 
off the boards, the things bad ice makes you do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a warm building, I think,'' he said.  
``Hopefully, we'll get it straightened away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were some familiar touches for longtime Leafs fans.  
</P>
<P>
	The 48th Highlanders, a regimental bagpipe and drum corps,  
performed in the pregame ceremony, just as they had done for 
decades at season openers at the Gardens. And public-address 
announcer Paul Morris was on the job, starting a new streak after 
announcing 1,561 consecutive games at the Gardens. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadiens, who left the historic Montreal Forum for the  
Molson Centre in 1996, were not daunted by the Leafs' new arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not much difference with all the new buildings,''  
Montreal captain Vincent Damphousse said. ``It's very similar to 
our building.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amid all the musings about past and future, Toronto backup  
goalie Glenn Healy offered an incontrovertible observation about 
the new arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``We always beat the Canadiens here,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
