<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street on Inflation Watch / Ticker Talk  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Despite widespread reports that inflation is  
dead and gone, investors in the Wall Street markets haven't stopped 
worrying about it. 
</P>
<P>
	On the contrary, they have pushed bond interest rates higher in  
recent weeks, registering heightened worries that inflationary 
pressures might be heating up again. 
</P>
<P>
	Most analysts think this scare isn't going to amount to much.  
Powerful disinflationary forces are still at work in the economy, 
they say, including the revolutionary efficiencies being wrought by 
the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	But the situation demonstrates that fears of inflation are still  
easily stirred among a generation of investors that hasn't 
forgotten the bad old days of the 1970s and early 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	``Inflation is dead and a wooden stake has been driven through  
its heart,'' says Jim Griffin at Aeltus Investment Management Inc. 
in Hartford, Conn. ``We know this for a fact because the world's 
leaders told us so. But markets can be recalcitrant, and so they 
have flirted lately with the idea that inflation lurks among the 
undead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rates on long-term Treasury bonds recently climbed to six-month  
highs above 5.4 percent, reflecting uneasiness in a market known 
for its sensitivity to inflation worries. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar currents have been visible in the stock market too.  
Utility stocks, for instance, have been retreating lately, amid 
talk that the Federal Reserve might be more inclined to tighten 
credit conditions, and less likely to ease, as 1999 progresses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Expectations of Fed easing have been taken completely out of  
the curve,'' says Stephen Roach, economist at Morgan Stanley Dean 
Witter &AMP; Co. ``U.S. fixed-income markets are now discounting a 
central bank that effectively remains on hold through midyear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The American economy has been stronger over the past few months  
than almost everyone thought it would be in the aftermath of 
currency and debt problems in Asia and Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, many observers who have been warning of the  
dangers of deflation, rather than inflation, say the threat of a 
worsening global economic slump hasn't gone away. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the end of last year, I expected that weaker profits would  
cause companies to cut back on employment and capital spending,'' 
says Edward Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche Bank Securities 
Inc. in New York. ``Instead, job growth and capital outlays remain 
robust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, Yardeni argues, ``By the second half a slowdown is  
likely, especially when compared to the current extraordinary pace. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expect that pricing will remain weak in energy and basic  
materials, and that disinflationary and deflationary pressures will 
spread to other sectors, especially technology, capital goods, 
consumer staples and consumer durables.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On balance, however, the scales on the Street definitely have  
tipped lately in the direction of inflation, rather than deflation, 
worries. 
</P>
<P>
	As Roach puts it, ``Growth is great. And for a fourth year in a  
row, the United States is getting much more of it than many ever 
dreamed possible, including the Fed. 
</P>
<P>
	``But the day is coming when growth will be bad -- when a fully  
employed U.S. economy has effectively run out of wiggle room to 
hold on a path of non-inflationary expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a world still perceived to be closer to deflation than  
reflation, most believe these considerations ring hollow. But as a 
vigorous U.S. economy continues to up the growth ante, the denial 
could finally crack.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
