<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Feb. 21, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	NATO Pressure Remains on Serbs  
</P>
<P>
	RAMBOUILLET, France (AP) -- The deadline for Kosovo peace talks  
may have been extended Saturday, but preparations for NATO military 
action will continue. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said a 
Nato threat will remain until parties at the talks accept all 
provisions for autonomy for ethnic Albanians. ``It would be a grave 
mistake for (Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic to miscalculate 
our intentions. ... We're not into endless extensions,'' she said. 
The United States and five other nations agreed to extend to 
Tuesday a deadline for the peace plan. NATO had threatened 
airstrikes against the Serbs if they did not reach an agreement 
with Albanian insurgents by noon Saturday. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Trains Stopped Because of Threat  
</P>
<P>
	HAVRE, Mont. (AP) -- Two passenger trains were halted in north  
central Montana on Saturday after Amtrak received a threat that a 
train was carrying radioactive material, federal authorities said. 
Sheriff Tim Solomon said eastbound and westbound Amtrak Empire 
Builder trains, which run between Chicago and Seattle, were stopped 
in Havre at about 6 p.m. EST. The trains were carrying a total of 
up to 350 passengers, who were being taken to a National Guard 
armory while crews made inspections. Inspectors did not immediately 
report finding any radioactive material. 

</P>
<P>
	London Police Accused of Racism  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- London's police force was riven by institutional  
racism that was a key factor in its failure to thoroughly 
investigate the slaying six years ago of a black teen-ager, a 
newspaper quoted a government report as saying. The Sunday 
Telegraph published excerpts of the report on the death of 
18-year-old Stephen Lawrence, who was stabbed to death in 1993. The 
inquiry, ordered in July 1997, has raised serious questions of 
police incompetence and highlighted racial antagonism in some 
rundown London districts. The Metropolitan Police have acknowledged 
they failed to investigate properly and apologized. 

</P>
<P>
	China Gov't Raids Dissident Party  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Police in China broke up a holiday party attended  
by about 50 members of a banned political opposition group and 
detained one of the activists, a human rights group said Sunday. 
Members of the China Democracy Party were entertaining others at 
the Spring Festival by singing and performing magic tricks at a tea 
house in the eastern city of Hangzhou on Saturday afternoon when 20 
police officers burst in and ended the celebration, the Information 
Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China said. 

</P>
<P>
	Movie Critic Gene Siskel Dies  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Film critic Gene Siskel, who wrote movie reviews  
for the Chicago Tribune and reviewed movies along with Roger Ebert 
on a syndicated television show, died Saturday. Siskel, 53, had 
surgery in May to remove a growth from his brain, but returned to 
``Siskel &AMP; Ebert'' soon afterward. He announced earlier this month 
he was taking time off from that show to spend time recuperating 
from the surgery. 

</P>
<P>
	NAACP May Sue Gun Makers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Since gun-related crimes hit minority  
communities at high rates across the country, the NAACP is 
considering joining the growing number of cities filing lawsuits 
against gun makers, NAACP President Kweisi Mfume said. He said he 
would present to the NAACP's 64-member Board of Directors several 
options, ranging from issuing a resolution that voices concern 
about guns to joining suits that filed by cities including Chicago 
and New Orleans. The NAACP also could file a separate suit. 

</P>
<P>
	Senators 4, Flyers 1  
</P>
<P>
	KANATA, Ontario (AP) -- Goaltender Ron Tugnutt continued his  
strong play and Radek Bonk scored his sixth winning goal of the 
season as the Ottawa Senators beat Philadelphia 4-1 Saturday night 
and climbed over the Flyers into first place in the NHL's Eastern 
Conference. Bonk's 12th goal of the season, his 100th NHL point, 
broke open a physical contest in which Philadelphia outshot Ottawa 
34-19. 

</P>
<P>
	Mavericks Bully Clippers 105-90  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Reserve forward Gary Trent got 13 of his 25  
points in the fourth quarter and finished with 16 rebounds as the 
Dallas Mavericks beat the Los Angeles Clippers 105-90 Saturday 
night. Michael Finley had 31 points, and starting guard Steve Nash 
scored his first nine points in the third quarter to help break 
open a close game and helping the Mavericks win for just the second 
time in their first 10 games. Nash finished with 13 points. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
