<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Telecom To Fight Takeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Communications ``Goliath'' Telecom Italia plans to  
challenge Olivetti's bold $58 billion takeover bid, which, if 
pulled off by a relative David of the telecommunications industry, 
would be one of Europe's biggest deals ever. 
</P>
<P>
	After a flurry of hastily called board meetings this weekend by  
Telecom Italia SpA and Telecom Italia Mobile, Europe's biggest 
mobile phone operator which is largely owned by Telecom Italia -- as 
well as by Olivetti SpA -- Telecom Italia issued a terse statement 
claiming there were holes in Olivetti's notice of its intention to 
acquire all of Telecom Italia's shares. 
</P>
<P>
	``Countermoves being studied,'' was how Milan daily Corriere  
della Sera on Sunday summed up the strategy at Telecom Italia, a 
former state monopoly and the world's sixth-largest phone company. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti's plan is ``that of David, who, with a handful of  
shares and indebting himself up to ears, makes an assault in the 
stock market,'' Corriere della Sera said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a few years ago, Olivetti was forced to resort to heavy  
layoffs because of its money-losing PC division. It eventually shed 
the computer division, plunging instead into telecommunications. 
</P>
<P>
	If Olivetti's filing with Italy's stock market regulatory body  
Consob -- made public Saturday -- fails to provide all the 
information required by law, as Telecom Italia has implied, then it 
would be free to try to counter the bid, perhaps by raising share 
prices and making a takeover too costly. 
</P>
<P>
	Among potential problems could be Olivetti's plan to raise some  
of the cash by selling off its mobile operator, fast-growing 
Omnitel Pronto Italia, as well as fixed-line operator Infostrada, 
to Mannesmann AG, a German industrial holding company. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian government granted permission for Omnitel's  
operating license on condition that it not be sold off for five 
years, and there is another year to go on that condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti and Mannesman control those two via a holding company  
50.1 percent owned by Olivetti and 49.9 percent owned by 
Mannesmann, the biggest rival to the former German telephone 
monopoly Deutsche Telekom. 
</P>
<P>
	In Germany on Sunday, Mannesmann said it will pay Olivetti $8.45  
billion for its stakes in Omnitel and Infostrada if the takeover 
bid succeeds. 
</P>
<P>
	Possibly further complicating maneuvers is that the Italian  
treasury ministry's so-called ``golden share'' in Telecom Italia, 
which was privatized in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	While holding just 3.4 percent of common stock, the ministry has  
veto powers over major decisions through 2000. Specifically, the 
state can block acquisition of more than 3 percent by an investor. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government isn't an inert spectator. It's vigilant and  
attentive on this affair,'' communications ministry undersecretary 
Vincenzo Vita said Sunday. ``There are risks of 'denationalization' 
for a great company like Telecom Italia, there are speculative 
risks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some union leaders have raised concern that such a costly  
operation would mean lots of job cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	But Olivetti's chief executive, Roberto Colaninno, with the  
company since 1996, claimed the takeover would be an 
``extraordinary occasion for the entire country'' and described the 
bid as ``an industrial operation, not financial speculation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He ruled out that there was a hidden ally behind the takeover  
bid, specifically Bell Atlantic Co., a U.S. communications company, 
or Italian financier Carlo De Benedetti, a former Olivetti 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	The bid relies heavily on debt financing from three U.S. banks --  
Chase Manhattan Bank, Lehman Brothers and Donaldson, Lufkin and 
Jenrette -- as well as Italy's Mediobanca. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
