<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots Deal Includes Moving Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The deal to bring the New England  
Patriots to Hartford includes expenses that were not part of the 
Legislative spending bill, including up to $750,000 the state must 
pay to physically relocate the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement took three months for more than a dozen lawyers to  
negotiate. The document was signed Feb. 12 by Gov. John G. Rowland 
and Patriots owner Robert Kraft and includes a number of aspects 
favorable to the Patriots that were not in the bill passed by the 
General Assembly in December. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The state will pick up the tab to move the team and its  
offices from Massachusetts to Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The state has already begun paying the costs of the $374  
million stadium project, including the team's legal fees and the 
hiring of architects. 
</P>
<P>
	If the deal falls through, the state is expected to pay all  
costs incurred up to that point. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The team will be allowed to negotiate an incentive agreement  
if it brings the stadium construction project in below budget. 
</P>
<P>
	--The team can use as collateral for loans the hundreds of  
millions of dollars in revenue expected over the 30-year term of 
the deal. The Hartford revenues would replace revenues from the 
Patriots' current home, Foxboro Stadium, to secure team debts. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not intended to be, 'Here's a source of revenue so you  
can build 50 new skyboxes in Foxboro,' '' said Brendan M. Fox Jr., 
executive director of the Capital City Economic Development 
Authority. ``It's to facilitate the move of the team to Hartford.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The waiver by the state, Connecticut officials say, made it  
easier to lock the Patriots into a 30-year deal without an escape 
once the stadium is built. If the team breaks the lease, they will 
be required to pay up to $400 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The state has made other concessions, including a provision in  
the development agreement that gives the Patriots the right to sue 
the state -- as if it was a private business -- in the event of a 
dispute over the revenue guarantees the state has made for the sale 
of club seats at the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The state is obligated to spend $280 million for the stadium  
construction, and $94 million for site cleanup and acquisition. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots must pick up the difference if the stadium exceeds  
$280 million, and invest at least $70 million for an NFL 
entertainment and dining pavilion and convention center as part of 
the Adriaen's Landing project. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement requires the stadium to be built by 2002 barring  
any uncontrollable circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	If that deadline is not met because the state failed to prepare  
the site or come up with the money, the Patriots can terminate the 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are several deadlines in the meantime at which the  
state or the team could walk away from the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The state must come up with a plan by Oct. 31 explaining how it  
will relocate a steam plant considered the main location for the 
stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Kraft and the state can consider building the stadium elsewhere  
if the polluted site can't be cleaned or the plant can't be 
relocated. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is also contingent upon approval from the National  
Football League. If the NFL does not give its blessing to the pact 
by October, both sides can walk away. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials say they will know whether the deal will come  
through by next February -- when the state must certify that it can 
release $280 million in bond funds that will be used to build the 
stadium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
