<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-21 11:11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Berlin Games a Boost for Brundage? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A construction company run by former IOC  
president Avery Brundage stood to benefit by the selection of 
Berlin as host of the 1936 Olympics, The New York Times reported 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The story also implicates two other past IOC presidents -- Henri  
de Baillet-Latour of Belgium and Sigfrid Edstrom of Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
	The story in the Times uses the current bribery scandal  
engulfing IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch as a backdrop, 
suggesting the problem facing the Olympic leadership is ``deeper, 
older and more profound than what has been presented as a shabby 
case of some Sydney and Salt Lake City payoffs for IOC votes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Times drew on the resources of the Simon Wiesenthal Center,  
a Los Angeles organization devoted to keeping alive the memory of 
the Holocaust and combating human rights abuses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Leaders of the Olympics violated their own rules; they sold  
their souls,'' said Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean and founder of the 
center. ``They injected politics into sports and they fudged the 
lines between business and amateurism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brundage was the head of the U.S. Olympic Committee at the time  
of the Berlin Games, an infamous Olympics that became a showcase 
for Nazi Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times reports the German Olympic Committee assured Brundage  
that his Chicago construction company would receive the bid to help 
build the German Embassy in Washington. However, the embassy was 
not built then because of World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Baillet-Latour was IOC president from 1925-42. The Times,  
acknowledging the difficulty in obtaining details, says his family 
ran a Belgian bank that was taken over by Deutsche Bank, which 
helped finance Auschwitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Edstrom succeeded Baillet-Latour as IOC president in 1942. The  
Times, citing research by the center, says he wrote Brundage in 
1933, complaining that U.S. Jews ``cause us so much trouble'' and 
make it ``impossible for our German friends to carry out the 
expensive preparations for the Olympic Games if all this unrest 
prevails.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990221.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-21 13:32:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sixth Dies From Ford Plant Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- A sixth Ford Motor Co. worker has died from  
injuries sustained in an explosion and fire at Ford Motor Co.'s 
sprawling Rouge complex. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Moritz, 46, had been in critical condition at the University  
of Michigan Hospital in Ann Arbor since the Feb. 1 explosion in 
Dearborn. He died Saturday night, hospital spokeswoman Andi 
McDonnell said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine other workers remain hospitalized.  
</P>
<P>
	A state investigator says a natural gas buildup led to the  
explosion at the complex, where 10,000 people make cars, car parts 
and steel. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990221.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-21 17:31:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Telecom To Fight Takeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- In a twist on the David-and-Goliath story,  
relatively small Olivetti SpA is attempting to orchestrate a $58 
billion takeover of Telecom Italia SpA, the world's sixth-largest 
phone company. 
</P>
<P>
	But Telecom Italia SpA isn't going to be taken down easily,  
issuing a terse statement that there were holes in Olivetti's 
notice of its intention to acquire all of Telecom Italia's shares. 
</P>
<P>
	``Countermoves being studied,'' was how Milan daily Corriere  
della Sera on Sunday summed up the strategy at Telecom Italia, a 
former state monopoly and the world's sixth-largest phone company. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti's plan is ``that of David, who, with a handful of  
shares and indebting himself up to ears, makes an assault in the 
stock market,'' Corriere della Sera said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a few years ago, Olivetti was forced to resort to heavy  
layoffs because of its money-losing PC division. It eventually shed 
the computer division, plunging instead into telecommunications. 
</P>
<P>
	If Olivetti's filing with Italy's stock market regulatory body  
Consob -- made public Saturday -- fails to provide all the 
information required by law, as Telecom Italia has implied, then it 
would be free to try to counter the bid, perhaps by raising share 
prices and making a takeover too costly. 
</P>
<P>
	Another possibility is a counter bid by Telecom Italia Mobile,  
Europe's biggest-mobile phone operator. Telecom Italia owns 60 
percent of TIM. 
</P>
<P>
	Among potential problems could be Olivetti's plan to raise some  
of the cash by selling off its mobile operator, fast-growing 
Omnitel Pronto Italia, as well as fixed-line operator Infostrada, 
to Mannesmann AG, a German industrial holding company. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian government granted permission for Omnitel's  
operating license on condition that it not be sold off for five 
years, and there is another year to go on that condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti and Mannesman control those two via a holding company  
50.1 percent owned by Olivetti and 49.9 percent owned by 
Mannesmann, the biggest rival to the former German telephone 
monopoly Deutsche Telekom. 
</P>
<P>
	In Germany on Sunday, Mannesmann said it will pay Olivetti $8.45  
billion for its stakes in Omnitel and Infostrada if the takeover 
bid succeeds. 
</P>
<P>
	Possibly further complicating maneuvers is that the Italian  
treasury ministry's so-called ``golden share'' in Telecom Italia, 
which was privatized in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	While holding just 3.4 percent of common stock, the ministry has  
veto powers over major decisions through 2000. Specifically, the 
state can block acquisition of more than 3 percent by an investor. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government isn't an inert spectator. It's vigilant and  
attentive on this affair,'' communications ministry undersecretary 
Vincenzo Vita said Sunday. ``There are risks of 'denationalization' 
for a great company like Telecom Italia, there are speculative 
risks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some union leaders have raised concern that such a costly  
operation would mean lots of job cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	But Olivetti's chief executive, Roberto Colaninno, with the  
company since 1996, claimed the takeover would be an 
``extraordinary occasion for the entire country'' and described the 
bid as ``an industrial operation, not financial speculation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He ruled out that there was a hidden ally behind the takeover  
bid, specifically Bell Atlantic Co., a U.S. communications company, 
or Italian financier Carlo De Benedetti, a former Olivetti 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	The bid is also relying heavily on debt financing from three  
U.S. banks -- Chase Manhattan Bank, Lehman Brothers and Donaldson, 
Lufkin and Jenrette -- as well as Italy's Mediobanca. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
