<DOCNO> APW19990221.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-21 17:22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gasoline Prices Drop Below $1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMARILLO, Calif. (AP) -- Gas prices didn't even flinch at moving  
below the $1 barrier, dropping more than 1 1/2 cents to set another 
new all-time low, an industry analyst said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The weighted average, including all grades and taxes, was 99.8  
cents per gallon Friday, down 1.61 cents from two weeks earlier, 
according to the Lundberg Survey of 10,000 stations nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Stil it may be nearing its low point, warned analyst Trilby  
Lundberg on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The price cutting is faster and deeper than it's been so far  
this year, but it is probably fizzing out,'' she said. ``Behind the 
average price fall are a few lonely no-change (prices) or price 
hikes here and there, from which I infer that retailers and their 
suppliers can't take it anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline prices have been steadily dropping for 1 1/2 years thanks  
to an oversupply of crude and refined oil products, creating the 
lowest prices in the history of the retail gas market when adjusted 
for inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	An increased spring demand for gasoline and more expensive  
seasonal antismog blending processes will probably bring the price 
declines to an end soon, Ms. Lundberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	The average prices at self-service stations was 93.63 cents per  
gallon for regular gasoline, $1.0475 for mid-grade and $1.1327 for 
premium. 
</P>
<P>
	Full-service prices were $1.4027 for regular, $1.4937 for  
mid-grade and $1.5680 for premium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
