<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Feb. 21, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	US, British Jets Attack Iraqi Bases  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- U.S. and British warplanes attacked an  
Iraqi missile base and two military communication sites today after 
Iraqi jets violated the no-fly zone, the U.S. military said. There 
was no immediate word on damage or casualties from the strikes near 
al-Amarah and Tallil. All the planes returned to their base, a 
statement from the U.S. Central Command said. Earlier, the official 
Iraqi News Agency said Iraqi air defenses may have shot down a 
Western military plane in southern Iraq. But the United States and 
Britain denied any planes were lost. 

</P>
<P>
	Still No Kosovo Peace Settlement  
</P>
<P>
	RAMBOUILLET, France (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine  
Albright, making scant headway toward a Kosovo peace settlement, 
said today that if neither Serbs nor ethnic Albanians accept the 
six-nation plan, NATO cannot carry through on its threat to attack 
Serb targets. With a new deadline set for Tuesday, Serb negotiators 
``are not engaging at all'' over the critical question of whether 
NATO peacekeepers would enforce the settlement, while the Kosovar 
Albanians must still be persuaded to sign on fully with the plan to 
give them greater autonomy in the Serb province, Albright said. 

</P>
<P>
	Pataki: First Lady Not Needed in NY  
</P>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) -- New York Gov. George Pataki has a  
message for Hillary Rodham Clinton as she mulls a run for the U.S. 
Senate in his state -- New York doesn't need her. ``She's thinking 
about moving to New York to straighten things out. Well, let me say 
with all due respect, we don't need liberal Democrats moving from 
Washington to the states to straighten out the states,'' Pataki 
said at a gathering of Missouri Republicans. ``We need Republicans 
from Missouri and New York and across the country moving to 
Washington to straighten it out.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Pentagon May Want Look at Iraq Book  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Defense Department agency, coming full  
circle, is telling former U.N. weapons inspector Scott Ritter once 
again that he may need to submit for pre-publication review a book 
expected to criticize the Clinton administration. A spokesman for 
the Defense Threat Reduction Agency said today that a letter was 
sent to Ritter's attorneys, saying that, under the contracts Ritter 
signed with the agency, any publication discussing the work he did 
hunting for illegal weapons in Iraq must first be submitted for 
governmental review. Ritter's lawyer calls the latest Pentagon 
position an attempt at intimidation. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Wants To Expand Gun Tracing  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In light of a report that showed at least half  
the guns used by juvenile criminals were bought illegally from 
licensed dealers, the Clinton administration wants more cities 
under a program that would trace these guns. The Bureau of Alcohol, 
Tobacco and Firearms released an analysis today of its Youth Crime 
Gun Interdiction Initiative. The program traced guns used in 76,260 
crimes in 27 cities over the past three years. President Clinton's 
budget request for fiscal 2000 includes an additional $11.2 million 
to expand the tracing program to 10 additional cities. 

</P>
<P>
	Arafat Eyes Statehood Consultations  
</P>
<P>
	GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Yasser Arafat said today he plans  
to consult with other countries regarding a plan to declare an 
independent Palestinian state, another indication the Palestinian 
leader may hold off on such a declaration this May. Western and 
Arab nations, concerned that such a declaration could help Israeli 
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu before May 17 Israeli elections, 
have urged Arafat to delay making any announcement. 

</P>
<P>
	India, Pakistan Vow Cooperation  
</P>
<P>
	LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) -- The prime ministers of Pakistan and  
India ended a two-day visit today vowing to give advance warning of 
ballistic missile tests. The two old enemies declared themselves 
nuclear powers by conducting underground tests in May. On the issue 
of Kashmir, the leaders said their two governments ``shall 
intensify their efforts to resolve all issues.'' They also agreed 
that their foreign ministers would meet occasionally and that the 
two sides would look for ways to cooperate in sharing information 
technology and look at ways to liberalize restrictive visa and 
travel laws. 

</P>
<P>
	Spurs Beat Pistons 85-64  
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Tim Duncan scored 17 points and grabbed 14  
rebounds, leading the San Antonio Spurs to an 85-64 victory over 
the cold-shooting Detroit Pistons today. San Antonio placed five 
players in double figures. Mario Elie had 16 points, Sean Elliott 
14, and David Robinson and Jarren Jackson 10 apiece. For the second 
time in a week, the Pistons set a team record for fewest points in 
a game. Monday, the Pistons scored 69 points in a loss to the New 
York Knicks. Detroit made 21 of 81 field goals (25.9 percent), a 
club record for San Antonio's defense. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  
</P>
</TEXT>
