<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Germans Finish 1-2 in Ski Jumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BISCHOFSHOFEN, Austria (AP) -- A daring Martin Schmitt produced a  
huge second jump to lead a 1-2 German finish Sunday in the large 
hill ski jumping event at the Nordic Ski World Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitt, this year's sensation on the World Cup circuit with  
seven victories, leaped 129.5 meters off the K120 hill in the 
second series to beat countryman Sven Hannawald and Japan's 
Hideharu Miyahira. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to take risks and I was very eager to win the gold,''  
Schmitt said after mastering rainy and foggy conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	The final result reversed the order of the first heat, when  
Hannawald jumped 127 meters and Schmitt 126. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitt's second jump was the longest of the day and gave him a  
total of 263.4 points. Hannawald, whose second leap also was 127 
meters, had 261.7 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone expected me to win and I was under a lot of  
pressure,'' said Schmitt, only in his third season as a ski jumper. 
Last year, Schmitt helped Germany win the silver medal in the team 
event at the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Miyahira had jumps of 125.5 and 128 meters for 258.8 points and  
third place. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitt, 21, has become hugely popular in Germany with his  
outgoing personality. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first jump was not 100 percent, but it was still quite  
long,'' Schmitt said. ``The second was super. I showed 
determination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitt became the first German world champion since Jens  
Weissflog won on the normal hill 10 years ago. Schmitt won on a 
hill where he lost the overall victory in the prestigious Four Hill 
Tour last month by slipping to a disappointing 14th place. 
</P>
<P>
	Janne Ahonen of Finland, the 1997 normal hill world champion and  
World Cup leader, took fourth place, ahead of Kazuyoshi Funaki of 
Japan, the Olympic normal hill champion, and Masahiko Harada, 
another Japanese who was the defending champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Alborn of Anchorage, Alaska, was the top American. He  
placed 27th after jumps of 109 and 101 meters for 173 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
