<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Economy Worst Since 1931 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Colombia's economy failed to grow last  
year, its worst performance since 1931, a leading association of 
banks and financial institutions said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``No growth, as has been calculated for last year, represents a  
true economic and social disaster,'' the National Association of 
Financial Institutions said in its weekly analysis of the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	If confirmed by official figures -- which have not yet been  
released -- it would be the first time the economy has failed to 
grow since 1931, when it shrank 1.6 percent, the association said. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials had predicted 2 percent growth for 1998,  
but the economy nose-dived during the past few months. Economists 
blame high interest rates, new taxes, guerrilla violence and low 
oil prices in the oil-producing South American nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The government predicts 1 percent growth for this year, but  
Armando Montenegro, head of the association, said zero growth is 
likely again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
