<HEADLINE> Madonna: I'm the Lucci of Grammys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The analogy isn't quite accurate, but Madonna  
characterizes her frustration over a career with just one Grammy 
award by saying, ``I'm the Susan Lucci of the music industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Comparing herself to the ``All My Children'' soap opera star  
nominated annually for best actress daytime Emmys but never a 
winner, Madonna won a Grammy for best video in 1991. She'll be up 
for five Grammys at Wednesday's awards show. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to get too attached to the idea of whether I'm  
going to win or not,'' Madonna says in Sunday's Daily News. ``If 
you get too attached to winning, then you get upset if you lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Madonna latest album, ``Ray of Light,'' is her biggest critical  
success and her best-selling album since 1989's ``Like a Prayer.'' 
At age 40, the pop star has embraced motherhood, a factor she sees 
as a possible reason for her multiple Grammy nominations. 
</P>
<P>
	``People do see me as a less threatening individual now,''  
Madonna said. ``Perhaps that has something to do with it. 
Motherhood has made me, in a lot of people's eyes, more respectable 
and acceptable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Madonna is nominated for record of the year, album of the year,  
dance recording, pop album and short form music video. 
</P>
</TEXT>
