<DOCNO> APW19990221.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-21 07:05:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov. Ventura Goes to Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tourists gawked and reporters thronged to his  
side. In a town of politicians, this was no ordinary one. Jesse 
Ventura, Minnesota's wrestler-turned-governor, had come to 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'd better be nice to me at the White House,'' said  
Ventura, reveling in the attention. ``Otherwise I might get Al's 
job that he wants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Al is Vice President Al Gore, who wants to get elected president  
in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	In a more serious vein, Ventura said he doesn't really want to  
be president, but he's still one of the stars of the National 
Governors' Association annual winter meeting that started Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the meeting, which includes dinner Sunday night at the  
White House, will be like ``going to school'' because of the chance 
to seek advice from fellow governors. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, who was elected last fall on the Reform Party ticket,  
made clear he intends to maintain his independence. He declined an 
invitation from Indiana Gov. Frank O'Bannon, to join a meeting of 
the Democratic governors Saturday afternoon and instead went to the 
Washington Mall to pose for pictures with the nation's other 
independent governor, Angus King of Maine. They were mobbed by 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here we are two independents and we're getting more press than  
those two Democratic and Republican parties ever thought of 
getting, because we're the movement,'' Ventura said. 
</P>
<P>
	Voters are tired of partisanship, said King. ``They just want  
the problems solved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, sitting for an interview with reporters, Ventura  
expressed an eclectic range of views on issues ranging from the 
role of the federal government to Indian policy. 
</P>
<P>
	On the federal government: ``I'm a great believer in power to  
the states. ... If there's a state that you don't agree with their 
policies, then you have 49 more states that you can go to live. If 
the federal government continues to grow and dominate, then that 
limits where you can go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He questioned how Indian tribes can claim to be sovereign at the  
same time they ask the government for help. ``Are you part of the 
United States or are you a sovereign nation? If you're your own 
sovereign nation, then take care of yourselves.'' Pressed to 
elaborate, he said he didn't have an opinion on whether the federal 
government should cut aid to tribes. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura said he respected the presidency but declined to say  
whether he respects President Clinton personally. ``I will just say 
that if I would have behaved in that manner, Minnesota wouldn't 
have to worry, I would have resigned.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990221.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-21 18:32:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Governors Give Bush a Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several Republican governors rallied Sunday to  
the side of George W. Bush, their Texas colleague who is 
increasingly likely to seek the presidency in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who says he's ``warming to the task'' of seeking the White  
House, was the hot commodity at the National Governors' Association 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he will run and be a great president,'' said Oklahoma  
Gov. Frank Keating, chairman of the Republican Governors' 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``He appeals to other-than-Republican voters, African-Americans  
and Hispanics,'' said Gov. John Rowland of Connecticut. ``It's not 
just his compassionate touch; he's very intelligent and politically 
astute.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even a Democratic supporter of Vice President Al Gore, Gov.  
Frank O'Bannon of Indiana, commended Bush for focusing on 
education. And he marveled at Bush's star appeal. ``I was walking 
into of one of these meetings when this big crowd started pushing 
and shoving, smashing me aside,'' O'Bannon said. ``Cameras and 
everything. It was him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As Bush swept past, the Indiana governor found himself  
apologizing for getting in the way. ``I said, `I'm sorry. I'm 
sorry,''' O'Bannon recalled with a laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan Gov. John Engler is Bush's unofficial point man with  
the governors. He called a handful of chief executives last week to 
ask if they would support Bush. The work continued Sunday. A senior 
Bush political adviser said at least two-thirds of the 31 GOP 
governors have offered their support if he runs for president. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush advisers, all of whom speak on condition of anonymity, say  
he is more likely than ever to run. A second aide said two weeks 
ago there was a good chance his boss would not seek the presidency; 
the aide had a different view Sunday: ``I can't see him not 
running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One thing that seems to bother Bush is the prospect of his  
personal life being scrutinized. Bush told Texas reporters Sunday 
that he will not expand on his earlier refusal to discuss whether 
he has ever used drugs. ``I will say that the rumors I'm hearing 
around here are totally ridiculous, and I would hope that the 
Washington press corps would be careful about gossip and rumors,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Engler said no formal endorsements would be made at this week's  
NGA meeting, but they could come later. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the keys to being successful is having governors very  
involved in the campaign,'' Engler said. 
</P>
<P>
	If he runs, Bush's backing won't be unanimous among the GOP  
governors. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of them, Mike Huckabee of Arkansas and Don Sundquist of  
Tennessee, are working for former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, 
who ran for president in 1996 and will try again. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson has another candidate in mind:  
himself. Thompson said Sunday he would like to run for president, 
but only if front-runners such as Bush and Elizabeth Dole faltered. 
Thompson, quoted recently as saying Bush has ``not done much as a 
governor,'' said Sunday that Bush would be a good candidate, though 
his record in Texas is not as strong as other governors. 
</P>
<P>
	New York Gov. George Pataki also is raising his national profile  
with the White House in mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the GOP governors Bush expects support from are Tom Ridge  
of Pennsylvania, Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts, Marc Racicot of 
Montana and Bill Graves of Kansas, who could become prospects for 
vice president or Cabinet posts. 
</P>
<P>
	Always coy about his intentions, Bush stopped short of  
confirming that Engler was doing his bidding in trying to 
accelerate a Bush bandwagon. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he is talking to people about what `warming to the task'  
means, that's fine by me,'' Bush said during a brief interview in a 
break between NGA sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor ate breakfast with Engler on Saturday, the  
opening day of the conference, and was meeting privately with 
several other state executives before the meeting ends Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	He also met with potential presidential campaign donors  
Saturday, part of an aggressive nationwide effort to build a 
fund-raising base that can be triggered the day he announces his 
intentions. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's Texas friends and allies of his father, former President  
George Bush, are already being recruited to join the campaign if 
Bush gives the green light. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush still intends by April to bow out of the campaign or take  
the next step by forming a presidential exploratory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The father of teen-age twin daughters, Bush sounds uneasy about  
the impact a campaign would have on his family. He said the 
daughters have told him, ``Dad, we love you. But don't do this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Bush quickly adds, ``Their opinion matters a lot to me, but  
the final decision rests with me. ... My girls mean a lot to me, 
but so does the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican and Democratic governors alike were guests at a White  
House dinner Sunday night, where President Clinton exchanged toasts 
with Gov. Thomas R. Carper, D-Del., chairman of the governors 
association. Dancing was on the card afterward, with music provided 
by the J Street Jumpers. 
</P>
<P>
	The president was scheduled to address the governors Monday  
morning and then join them for another dinner Monday night at the 
National Building Museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
