<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Feb. 21, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Albright, Albanians Talk Kosovo Deal  
</P>
<P>
	RAMBOUILLET, France (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright  
talked at length today with ethnic Albanians, seeking to lock in 
their tentative approval of a peace plan for Kosovo. Her aim was to 
put additional pressure on the Serbs to accept the deployment of 
NATO peacekeepers to enforce any peace agreement reached for the 
embattled province. But she met with four Albanian leaders for 
about 90 minutes without getting their final approval for the plan 
proposed by the six-nation Contact Group on the Balkans. The 
Contact Group -- consisting of the United States, France, Britain, 
Germany, Italy and Russia -- agreed to extend the deadline for peace 
talks from noon yesterday until 3 p.m. on Tuesday after some 
progress was reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspects in Ireland Attacked Nabbed  
</P>
<P>
	DUNDALK, Ireland (AP) -- Police on both sides of the Irish border  
arrested suspects today in last year's car bombing in Omagh, the 
deadliest terrorist strike in Northern Ireland's 30-year conflict. 
In the Irish Republic, five men were detained under Ireland's 
Offenses Against the State Act anti-terrorist laws that permits 
suspects to be kept in custody for up to 48 hours before being 
either charged or released. Detectives in Northern Ireland also 
made some arrests, but would only say that a ``number'' of people 
were being questioned. Police have so far arrested more than 60 
suspects, but no one has been charged in connection with the Aug. 
15 car bombing that killed 29 people and wounded 370. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq Says It May Have Downed Plane  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- The official Iraqi News Agency reported  
that Iraqi air defenses may have shot down a Western military plane 
in southern Iraq, but the United States and Britain denied any 
planes were lost. ``Our air defenses have confronted the enemy 
aircraft and one of them seems to have been shot,'' INA quoted a 
military spokesman as saying. A Pentagon spokesman said that ``all 
morning flights were uneventful.'' Meanwhile, Gen. Henry H. 
Shelton, chairman of the U.S. joint chiefs of staff, made his first 
stop on a Persian Gulf tour to discuss Iraqi threats against its 
neighbors in the aftermath of U.S. and British strikes. Shelton met 
today with Saudi Defense Minister Prince Sultan. 

</P>
<P>
	Animosity Lingers for Clinton, GOP  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and congressional leaders  
mark the beginning of the post-impeachment Congress with a White 
House meeting Tuesday, but don't expect much beyond a shaky image 
of bipartisan cooperation. The session will be the first meeting in 
19 months between the president and Republican leaders. While both 
sides feel pressure from the public to demonstrate they are dealing 
with the nation's business, Republican distrust for Clinton runs 
deep, as do partisan divisions on Social Security and tax cuts. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Mass Grave Found in Algeria  
</P>
<P>
	ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Authorities have pulled 70 bodies from a  
well used as a mass grave on the outskirts of the Algerian capital, 
a newspaper reported. The bodies were retrieved near Oued Allel, 
the newspaper Liberte reported. The decision to search the well was 
based on information provided by a member of the Armed Islamic 
Group who turned himself in to police, the report said. An 
estimated 75,000 people have been killed since the start of the 
insurgency in 1992. 

</P>
<P>
	Germany Honors 'Thin Red Line'  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Terrence Malick's World War II epic ``The Thin Red  
Line,'' took top honors today at the Berlin International Film 
Festival. Spanish actress Angela Molina, who chaired the 
international jury, said the vote was unanimous for Malick's poetic 
film, which contrasts brutal battle scenes with beautiful nature 
shots and carries a strong anti-war message. ``It was important for 
us, that testament,'' she said. 

</P>
<P>
	More Delays for Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Two months after launching the  
foundation of its new space station, NASA isn't sure how long it 
will take to finish the job because its biggest partner, the 
Russian Space Agency, has fallen behind schedule yet again. The 
Russian Space Agency's main contribution is a control module that's 
meant to double as the crew quarters. The Russian module should 
have soared in April 1998, then in December 1998, then in April 
1999, then in July 1999. Now an engineering evaluation by NASA 
shows that despite $60 million in U.S. assistance, the 43-foot 
compartment won't be ready to fly before September. 

</P>
<P>
	Kafelnikov Wins Netherlands Tennis  
</P>
<P>
	ROTTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Yevgeny Kafelnikov closed in on  
tennis' No. 1 ranking today, beating Tim Henman 6-2, 7-6 (7-3) to 
win the ABN AMRO tournament. The win moved Kafelnikov, ranked No. 
2, received 260 ATP points for the victory, within 85 of top-ranked 
Pete Sampras. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  
</P>
