<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Wins Swimming Backstroke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Germany's Antje Buschschulte completed a sweep of  
the women's backstroke events at the World Cup swimming meet, 
winning the 100-meter race in 1 minute, .06 seconds Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Buschschulte, who won the 50 and 200 races Saturday, finished  
far ahead of Alena Nyvltova of the Czech Republic, the runner-up at 
1:01.16. 
</P>
<P>
	World record-holder Susan O'Neill swam another brilliant  
200-meter butterfly. 
</P>
<P>
	The Australian, who set the record of 2:05.37 last week, won  
Sunday's race at 2:05.70, more than two seconds ahead of Denmark's 
Mette Jacobsen. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain's Susan Rolph won both the 100 freestyle and 100 medley  
races. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Keller, James Hickman, Jorg Hoffmann and Fredrick  
Deburghgraeve all won their second golds of the two-day 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's Keller added the 200 medley to his 100 medley victory.  
Hickman, of Britain, won the 100 butterfly after taking the 200 
butterfly. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoffman, of Germany, took the 1,500 freestyle, after winning the  
400 freestyle, and Belgium's Deburghgraeve won the 100 
breaststroke, after taking the 50 breaststroke. 
</P>
</TEXT>
