<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Life Changed for Tornado Survivors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- A year after seven tornadoes swept  
through central Florida, killing 42 people, two survivors are doing 
the best they can to go on with drastically changed lives. 
</P>
<P>
	The twisters came in the middle of the night of Feb. 22-23,  
1998, when most people were sleeping and never heard any warnings. 
They tore a 50-mile path, causing $36.8 million in damage as they 
damaged or destroyed more than 3,600 homes and businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind the physical devastation are emotional bruises that  
survivors are still nursing. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Kahn lost his wife and became a crusader for a weather  
warning system in the mobile park where he lives. Shirley Driver 
lost her house and was forced to give up the two 
great-grandchildren she was raising. She now lives in an apartment 
by herself. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	At the Ponderosa RV Campground in Kissimmee, the worst-hit area  
where more than a dozen people were killed, shiny new mobile homes 
are lined up where heaps of twisted metal, siding and shredded 
fabric lay only a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of the park's residents, many of them survivors of the  
tornadoes, chatted and played shuffleboard recently under a clear 
blue Florida sky. 
</P>
<P>
	But the scars from that deadly night were still there -- on the  
still-bruised forearms of Kahn, 78, who spent eight days in an 
intensive care unit. His wife, Theda, 72, was killed when she was 
thrown from their mobile home. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple had come down from St. Clair Shores, Mich., each  
winter for 16 years. This winter, Kahn returned with a new trailer 
despite his grievous loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did everything together,'' Kahn said of his wife. ``We had  
a good life together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some newly arrived residents of the mobile home park greeted,  
hugged and kissed Kahn as he played shuffleboard. Some discussing 
weekend weather wondered whether strong winds were expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the winds get going, people get nervous,'' said neighbor  
Loraine Ruddy, 59, who escaped serious injury in last year's 
twisters. 
</P>
<P>
	Kahn has made it his mission to make sure the mobile home park  
gets a weather warning system. He has lobbied state and county 
officials and hopes the park is one of five that state emergency 
officials use for a pilot program. 
</P>
<P>
	He wants construction of a brick wall around the shower rooms at  
the park that would shelter him and his friends in the event of 
another tornado. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I moved elsewhere I wouldn't know anybody,'' Kahn said.  
``This place is like a second home.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Waldick was called the ``Miracle Boy'' after he  
survived being sucked out of his great-grandmother's two-bedroom 
home. It was smashed to pieces and Jonathan, then 18 months old, 
was hurled into the branches of a fallen oak tree. 
</P>
<P>
	He was saved by a mattress that wrapped around him and protected  
him from the slabs of fallen wallboard and plywood. He suffered no 
more than a few scratches on his chin, but his life changed 
dramatically anyway as his great-grandmother was forced to give him 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I lost my house. I lost my car. I lost my  
great-grandchildren,'' Mrs. Driver said. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy and his half-sister, Destiny, are now living with other  
relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan had been living with Mrs. Driver since October 1997  
when his mother turned him over to her. Mrs. Driver was also 
raising 4-year-old Destiny. 
</P>
<P>
	After the tornadoes, the children's mother took custody of them  
for a short time before they were placed in foster care because 
their mother was investigated for abuse. Child welfare workers told 
the 69-year-old Mrs. Driver that she was too old to be raising the 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	It was all too stressful for Mrs. Driver, who spent several  
months living in Utah with her daughter after she almost had a 
nervous breakdown. After living in successive foster homes, the 
children were put up for adoption last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Driver's daughter and son-in-law, Earline and Dan Riddle,  
decided to adopt them last December and the children now live in 
Salt Lake City, where they are doing well, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Destiny remembers everything from the night of the tornadoes.  
Mrs. Driver's memory is less vivid since she was hit in the head 
with a wood plank. All three of them get nervous whenever they hear 
a plane flying overhead -- the sound too much like a tornado. 
</P>
<P>
	Deciding not to rebuild her home, Mrs. Driver is now living by  
herself in a two-bedroom apartment. The home's lot sits empty 
between two cinderblock houses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Life turns in funny ways,'' Mrs. Driver said. ``It's God's  
will.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
