<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, New Zealand Talk Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUEENSTOWN, New Zealand (AP) -- The prime ministers of Australia  
and New Zealand said Sunday that their countries are considering 
extending a free trade agreement to South America and possibly the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian Prime Minister John Howard and New Zealand Prime  
Minister Jenny Shipley discussed the plan in two hours of talks 
Saturday in the south island resort town of Queenstown. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipley said both countries had benefited from their closer  
economic relationship -- or CER -- signed 16 years ago, and that 
other nations have expressed interest in the trade accord. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've both had a number of visitors from South America in the  
past 12 months and they've openly talked about CER,'' Shipley told 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Perhaps that is the next step for CER -- to get the quantum  
leap that we saw we received in the early stages of this trading 
agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Howard said increased liberalization of trade should continue to  
be a goal for countries such as New Zealand and Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every opportunity there is to expand the horizons of freer  
trade we should grab,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But he ruled out any immediate action.  
</P>
<P>
	Shipley said the main effort this year would be in establishing  
a broad-based World Trade Organization round of negotiations, and 
then a strong Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit meeting in 
November in Auckland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
