<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Pitcher, Congressman Mizell Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HIGH POINT, N.C. (AP) -- Former congressman and major league  
baseball pitcher Wilmer ``Vinegar Bend'' Mizell died Sunday while 
visiting his wife's family in Texas. He was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Family members believed Mizell died from the lingering effects  
of a heart attack suffered four months ago while attending a high 
school football game, his son, David Mizell, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mizell, who lives in Midway, served from 1968 to 1974 as the  
U.S. representative from North Carolina's 5th District. 
</P>
<P>
	Mizell acquired his nickname from the place where he grew up,  
Vinegar Bend, Ala. From 1952-62, Mizell pitched for the St. Louis 
Cardinals, Pittsburgh Pirates and New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1960, Mizell helped the Pirates win the World Series. He  
posted a 13-5 record with a 3.12 ERA that season with the Cardinals 
and Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	Mizell died in Kerrville, Texas, while he and his second wife,  
Ruth Cox Mizell, were visiting her family. The couple also had a 
home in Alexandria, Va., David Mizell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral services will be Thursday in Midway.  
</P>
<P>
	After retiring from baseball, Mizell was elected as a  
commissioner in Davidson County. 
</P>
<P>
	After he lost his U.S. House seat in 1974, President Gerald Ford  
appointed the Republican as Assistant Secretary of Commerce for 
Economic Development. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1982, Ronald Reagan picked him to become an assistant  
secretary of agriculture for governmental affairs -- the agency's 
top lobbyist in Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
