<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Two Spaniards were kidnapped while  
installing telephone cables and an antennae for a company in rural 
Colombia, authorities said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Luis Garcia and Marcos Gallegos Jimenez were kidnapped  
Friday by a group of men wearing military uniforms in Supia, 115 
miles northwest of the capital, Bogota. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities presume the kidnappers are members of the  
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, the country's largest rebel 
group, though they have not ruled out common criminals, 
paramilitaries or other guerrilla groups, said Jose Alfredo 
Escobar, head of the government anti-kidnapping office. 
</P>
<P>
	Escobar said a total of 15 kidnapped foreigners are currently  
being held. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Colombia's economy failed to grow last  
year, its worst performance since 1931, a leading association of 
banks and financial institutions said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``No growth, as has been calculated for last year, represents a  
true economic and social disaster,'' the National Association of 
Financial Institutions said. 
</P>
<P>
	If confirmed by official figures -- which have not yet been  
released -- it would be the first time the economy has failed to 
grow since 1931, when it shrank 1.6 percent, the association said. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists blame high interest rates, new taxes, guerrilla  
violence and low oil prices in the oil-producing South American 
nation. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Gunmen in Brazil shot a trade union  
leader, who is a key witness in an alleged corruption scandal 
involving city politicians, media reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Afonso Jose da Silva, president of Sao Paulo's street vendors  
trade union, was shot four times in the organization's headquarters 
Saturday, said the CBN radio station. 
</P>
<P>
	Silva was in a serious condition Sunday, said Sueli Maira da  
Silva, a spokesman for the Sacred House of Compassion hospital in 
this city. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Silva alleged council staff had extorted  
money from street vendors to finance politicians' election 
campaigns, the station said. Fifty council workers were 
subsequently suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Fishermen along Mexico's northern Pacific  
coast say nine gray whales have been found dead in a bay where the 
giant sea mammals migrate annually to mate and give birth, the 
government news agency said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Miguel Mendez Sanchez, head of a fishermen's coalition in Baja  
California Sur state, said government teams should remove the huge 
carcasses because fishermen fear they could contaminate Magdalena 
Bay, the Notimex agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are trying to determine the cause of the deaths.  
Mendez said that while whale deaths are not unusual, local 
fishermen do not recall seeing so many die in one season, Notimex 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, a Mexico City environmental organization, the Group  
of 100, urged the government to investigate the deaths of seven 
whales along the coasts of Sinaloa, Sonora and Baja California Sur 
states, including three in Magdalena Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	It charged that a cyanide-based chemical used by smugglers to  
mark drug shipment points could be to blame. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Police arrested 10 Greenpeace activists who  
climbed onto Mexico City's Angel of Independence monument Sunday to 
hang banners protesting genetic engineering of plants and animals, 
the environmental group said. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters, wearing masks and white overalls, hung a sign  
reading ``The corn is ours'' in front of a statue of Mexico's 
founding father, Miguel Hidalgo, and draped a large banner reading 
``No to genetic imperialism'' from the base of the monument. 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrived an hour after the signs went up and arrested the  
protesters, Greenpeace said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The group accused the United States of leading efforts to block  
an agreement at the Biosafety Protocal summit being held in 
Colombia. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States -- backed by Canada, Australia, Uruguay and  
Argentina -- hopes to protect a rapidly growing industry whose 
proponents insist bioengineering is a safe, proven and 
environmentally sound technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Biotech companies genetically manipulate plants and animals to  
speed their growth, make them more resistant to disease or make 
them more attractive. Developing nations fear genetically 
engineered crops could have devastating effects on their 
agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
