<HEADLINE> Yankees' Williams Glad To Be Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Bernie Williams is glad to still be on the  
New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	The center fielder reported to the team's spring training  
facility on Sunday, returning to the team he nearly left during the 
offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's good to know that I'm back here where I know the system,  
I know the coaches and I know the organization,'' Williams said. 
``I don't have to start all over again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The AL batting champion was on the verge of signing with Boston  
when Yankees owner George Steinbrenner's last-minute pitch resulted 
in a seven-year, $87.5 million deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fame, security, money, whatever, it's good -- but it's not what  
really drives me as a player and I think that will never change,'' 
Williams said. ``The fact is I'm a baseball player. That's what I 
love doing, that's what drives me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams received a loud ovation when he took the field for a  
35-minute batting practice session with teammate Darryl Strawberry. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes you feel great,'' Williams said. ``Still, if I play  
bad, they're going to run me out of town. I need to perform and 
play up to my expectations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams had a stellar 1998 season, hitting .339 with 26 homers  
and 97 RBI during the Yankees' march toward a 125-win season and 
the team's second World Series title in three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Most people, however, including Williams and Yankees manager Joe  
Torre felt the outfielder's final appearance for the Yankees had 
come in Game 4 of last fall's World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to have him back with a smile, instead of coming in  
like he did last year worrying about causing a distraction in the 
clubhouse,'' Torre said. ``It's good to be able to put that to 
sleep.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Williams called the acquisition of Cy Young Award  
winner Roger Clemens ``a great addition,'' the deal did have a 
sobering impact. In that trade with Toronto, the Yankees gave up 
18-game winner David Wells, a key component last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter how great a year you had, you're as expendable as  
the next guy,'' Williams said. ``The biggest example came several 
days ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Most of the position players, who are scheduled to report  
on Monday and formally work out Tuesday, are already in Tampa. 
Derek Jeter, Tino Martinez, Chili Davis and Chuck Knoblauch are 
already working out at Legends Field or the Yankees' nearby minor 
league complex. ... Hideki Irabu may have lost a friend when Wells 
was traded, but likely gained a mentor in Clemens. Through his 
interpreter, Irabu said he planned on watching and learning from 
Clemens regarding conditioning and game day preparation. ``He's a 
pretty good guy to watch,'' Torre said, who is seeking more 
consistency from Irabu this season. ... Clemens' first full day at 
Legends Field included a workout just after 7 a.m., the regular 
spring session at 11 a.m. and a photo shoot at 4 p.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
