<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Critical of Serbs at Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RAMBOUILLET, France (AP) -- The Kosovo peace talks moved into  
overtime Sunday with Western nations -- trying to salvage a deal and 
hold off NATO airstrikes -- split over Serbian rejection of foreign 
peacekeeping troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Western officials mediating the talks said Saturday the deadline  
had been extended from Saturday noon until 3 p.m. (9 a.m. EST) 
Tuesday because ``very substantial progress'' had been made on the 
political part of a three-year interim agreement for Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement came after U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine  
Albright and ministers from five European countries spent a day in 
heated discussions with the Serb and ethnic Albanian sides in the 
14th-century Chateau de Rambouillet near Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright returned to the chateau Sunday, saying ``there is an  
awful lot of work to be done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We always knew that these were going to be very difficult  
discussions,'' Albright said. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
Albright would meet with the ethnic Albanians. She had no meetings 
planned with the Serbs, though her schedule was fluid. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright made clear Saturday who she felt was preventing a deal,  
accusing the Serb negotiators, led from Belgrade by Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic, of ``evasion and delay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I would hope that Milosevic will wake up and smell the  
coffee,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be a grave mistake for Milosevic to miscalculate our  
intentions. ... We're not into endless extensions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said the Serbs had shown a lack of desire to negotiate  
on the main sticking point: a NATO force of up to 30,000 
international troops to enforce a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Serbs' refusal to even consider the peace implementation  
force is largely responsible for our failure to reach an 
agreement,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright also said that until the Serbs accept all provisions,  
``the preparations for NATO military action will continue.'' NATO 
has said it would strike against Serb-led Yugoslavia if a deal was 
not reached at the conference which started Feb. 6. 
</P>
<P>
	British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, in remarks contrasting  
sharply with Albright who put the blame squarely on the Serbs, said 
Kosovo Albanians are also to blame. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the moment we have on the Belgrade side a government that  
is accepting the constitutional settlement for a self-governing 
Kosovo, but we don't have the Kosovar side that is doing so,'' Cook 
said on the British Broadcasting Corp.'s Breakfast with Frost 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	``In that context, airstrikes on Belgrade are not going to  
help,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav media Sunday presented the decision to extend the  
deadline as a triumph for Belgrade, which managed to split the 
foreign powers mediating the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Discord in the Contact Group,'' said the headline on the  
state-controlled newspaper Politika, referring to the United States 
and five European powers conducting the conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Milan Milutinovic, the Serbian president, said late Saturday  
that more time will be needed to solve the Kosovo problem ``that is 
several decades old.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also indicated that Serbia would allow foreign troops, but  
only after the political part of the agreement was signed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can discuss everything after the agreement,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	About 2,000 people have died and hundreds of thousands been  
displaced in a year of fighting in Kosovo. Ethnic Albanians make up 
90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million population, and most favor 
independence. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed peace plan grants the southern Serbian province  
wide autonomy. It calls for most Serbian security forces to 
withdraw from the region and the disarming of ethnic Albanian 
rebels. But it keeps the province within Yugoslav borders. 
</P>
<P>
	An annex to the plan provides for the NATO troops, including  
4,000 Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has come out strongly against the use of force. On  
Saturday, Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov echoed those 
sentiments in a telephone conversation with British Prime Minister 
Tony Blair, the Interfax news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, China joined Russia in its opposition of airstrikes  
against Yugoslavia if a Kosovo peace agreement cannot be reached, a 
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	China disapproves of any military action against Yugoslavia and  
instead wants a peaceful solution ``on the basis of respecting the 
sovereignty and territorial integrity of Yugoslavia and ensuring 
the lawful interests of all ethnic groups in the Kosovo region,'' 
the state-run Xinhua News Agency quoted spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue as 
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
