<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Workers Unfazed by Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Salt Lake Organizing Committee has  
hired only 170 of the 800 employees it will need for the 2002 
Winter Games, and the bribery scandal apparently has not slowed the 
flow of resumes. 
</P>
<P>
	Human Resources director Ed Eynon said only one prospective  
employee and one volunteer hesitated because of the scandal, but 
both later changed their minds and joined. 
</P>
<P>
	The worst corruption scandal in Olympics history began unfolding  
in December. An investigating panel said this month that two 
executives of the bid committee spent more than $1 million on 
International Olympic Committee members and their relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Working for SLOC is a risky proposition -- a three-year or  
four-year stint with a guaranteed layoff after the 2002 Olympic 
Games. Yet the organizing committee has little trouble attracting 
applicants. 
</P>
<P>
	``How often do the Olympic Games even come to the United  
States?'' asked Karen Koppel, an architect from Boulder, Colo., who 
moved to Utah to work for SLOC. ``This was a once-in-a-lifetime 
opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Koppel said her SLOC salary is comparable to what she earned in  
Colorado. She'll have to find a new job when the Olympics are over, 
but that's just part of the adventure. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, SLOC has 14 jobs posted on its Web site and hundreds  
more will appear in coming months and years. Most of the remaining 
positions are lower and midlevel jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've hired the majority of our directors up front because a  
lot of the planning and execution has to be done by the 
leadership,'' Eynon said. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC is seeking those with what Eynon calls ``world-class  
experience,'' and many of the jobs have technical requirements, 
such as experience running racing venues. 
</P>
<P>
	Eynon said he expects to draw about 80 percent of the staff from  
Utah and 20 percent from other states or countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``All things being equal, it's nice to have a Utahn in a  
position, because the Games are here,'' Eynon said. 
</P>
<P>
	The pay is better than for most similar jobs in Utah, although  
it's comparable to national rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretaries make between $25,000 and $30,000, and the directors  
of some 45 functions within SLOC earn upward of $80,000 each. 
SLOC's six or seven managing directors, the next tier in the SLOC 
hierarchy, make anywhere from $115,000 to $175,000 each. 
</P>
<P>
	The organization's senior vice presidents, who are directly  
beneath president Mitt Romney, earn a little less than $200,000 
each. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney, hired Feb. 11, said he'll be paid the same salary as his  
predecessor, $285,000 a year, but he won't collect the money until 
the games are over and it's clear they are in the black. 
</P>
<P>
	He notes that most of the senior staff members are earning less  
than they would in the corporate world. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are other rewards here beside career advancement or  
money,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
