<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-21 10:52:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toyotas, Hondas Popular for Thieves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Toyota and Honda make some of the nation's  
best-selling cars. And the nation's thieves have noticed. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, 21 of the 25 most-stolen vehicles were made by the  
Japanese automakers; nearly all were Toyota Camrys and Honda 
Accords. For the first time, the top 10 most-stolen vehicles were 
all Toyotas and Hondas. 
</P>
<P>
	The good news for owners of all makes is that claims for major  
vehicle thefts were down about 22 percent last year, according to 
CCC Information Services Inc., which tracks trends in theft and 
other vehicle damage claims for the insurance industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's very significant,'' said Jack Rozint, senior vice  
president of CCC. He credited police agencies' heightened focus on 
stolen car parts and manufacturers' increased practice of marking 
many parts with the vehicle's identification number, which makes 
tracing stolen parts easier. 
</P>
<P>
	According to CCC's annual list, to be released Monday, the  
most-stolen car for the second straight year was the 1989 Camry, 
followed by the '88 and '90 Camrys. The most-stolen Honda was the 
'94 Accord EX at No. 4. Thirteen Accords ranked among the top 25. 
</P>
<P>
	The formula that put Camrys and Accords atop the list is simple:  
There were a lot of them sold, they last a long time and, as a 
result, their parts are in high demand. It's a lot easier and more 
profitable to fence a fuel pump from an '89 Camry than an '89 Yugo. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of those models also is popular because many of its parts  
are interchangeable over several model years. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you can steal a car and the parts can be used across  
five, six, seven or eight model years, obviously those parts have a 
high value,'' Rozint said. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota spokesman John McCandless said the dubious distinction  
was a credit to the longevity of the Camry and Accord. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our cars and the others on the list are extremely durable,''  
he said. ``It's not unusual for me to talk to the owner of a 
Corolla or Camry who has a 9-year-old car with 200,000 miles on it 
and it's still going strong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Camry was the top-selling car in the United States for the  
past two years, followed by the Accord. McCandless noted that the 
top Camry on the most-stolen list was 10 years old and said 
customers shouldn't be wary about buying a new model for fear of 
theft. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda spokesman Art Garner said Accord thefts are ``pretty  
average'' if calculated on a per-capita basis. ``On total volume, 
they come out just like the sales figures: the Accord and Camry 
rise to the top.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Honda added an antitheft system that includes an electronically  
coded key beginning with the '98 Accords. 
</P>
<P>
	Only four models by U.S. automakers appeared on the 1998 list --  
the fewest in years -- and none was ranked among the top 10. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oldsmobile Cutlass disappeared from the list for the first  
time since CCC made it public in 1990. The Cutlass, a big seller in 
the 1980s, still made the most-stolen lists for some states, 
including Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	The most stolen U.S. nameplates were the '97 Ford F150 XL 4x2  
pickup at No. 14, followed in order by the '95 Ford Mustang, the 
'89 Chevrolet Caprice, and at No. 22, the Chevy C/K series 4x2 
pickup. The most-stolen sport utility vehicle was the '93 Jeep 
Grand Cherokee 4x4 at No. 29. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Insurance Crime Bureau in October reported that the  
Honda Accord was the most stolen vehicle nationwide in 1997. It was 
followed by the Toyota Camry, Oldsmobile Cutlass, Honda Civic and 
Ford Mustang. 
</P>
<P>
	The bureau, which also tracks thefts for insurance companies,  
combines theft reports for all years of a particular make and 
model. CCC ranks the cars by specific model years and 
equipment-trim lines. 
</P>
<P>
	CCC's ranking also is based only on those stolen vehicles that  
were never recovered or were stripped to the point that they were a 
total loss. It does not include temporary ``joy ride'' thefts. 
</P>
<P>
	Regional theft rankings can vary widely from the national trend.  
</P>
<P>
	In Michigan, where American cars are still king, the 1995  
Plymouth Neon ranked No. 1 and its Dodge twin ranked second. 
Illinois was partial to Chevys: the top three were the '87, '89 and 
'88 Caprices. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas thieves favored the '97 Ford F150 XL 4x2 pickup, followed  
by the '98 version. And in New York, two sport utility vehicles 
made the list: the pricey '97 Toyota 4x4 at No. 4 and the '97 
Toyota Runner 4x4 at No. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	CCC, based in Chicago, tracked 102,635 vehicle thefts that  
resulted in a total loss last year, as well as crash and other 
damage claims. That's down from 131,278 in 1987. Those numbers 
reflect the vast majority, but not all, of such claims filed 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	CCC handled about 1.7 million of the industry's 2.2 million  
total-loss claims last year, including those from crashes. A 
vehicle is considered a total loss if its salvage value and the 
cost to repair combined exceed its fair market value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990221.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-21 15:22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Still High in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Although the worst of Asia's financial crisis  
appears over, there's still plenty of pain going around. Some 
economies remain mired in recession, millions of people are without 
work, and already-low wages are lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebound from the devastating collapse that began in Thailand  
in July 1997 and spread across Asia and then to Russia and Brazil 
will be slow and uneven, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any optimism one has on the region has to be hedged, has to be  
cautious,'' said Russell Jones, chief Asia economist for the 
investment bank Lehman Brothers in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The economic crisis was caused by heavily indebted banking  
systems, overvalued currencies, excessive government spending and 
over-reliance on foreign loans. ``Crony capitalism'' -- the tight 
links between government officials, bankers and favored companies -- 
also gets blame. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korea, forced to seek a $58 billion bailout from the  
International Monetary Fund, is considered the best prospect for 
recovery from the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's ample evidence that Korea is turning around nicely,  
and that's probably the big success story at the moment,'' Jones 
said. ``Elsewhere, the picture is a lot less rosy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some experts predict South Korea's economy will grow by around 2  
percent this year, following a contraction of nearly 6 percent in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Although critics say South Korea has not gone far enough to  
reform its business conglomerates, known as ``chaebol,'' whose 
heavy debts were blamed for dragging down the economy, most 
analysts say the recovery looks real. 
</P>
<P>
	But unemployment hit 7.9 percent in December, and many Koreans  
are tempering any optimism. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, the situation is getting better, but I'm afraid  
that the government and the media may be exaggerating the recovery 
pace,'' said Lee Jong-in, 35, who runs a small trading company in 
the capital, Seoul. ``I think it would take many years to see the 
economy become solid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists say the rest of the region, too, has weathered  
the worst. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Schulte, chief Asian investment strategist for ING Baring  
Securities (Hong Kong) Ltd., puts it this way: ``We're looking at a 
very, very mild recovery in 1999'' -- except for Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan, the world's second largest economy, is stuck in its worst  
recession since World War II and has been unable to help pull 
neighboring economies out of their gloom. Japan's joblessness rate 
hit a postwar high of 4.4 percent in November, easing only to 4.3 
percent in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Although some government officials predict the Japanese economy  
will grow this year, private economists and many Japanese have 
their doubts. Critics say the government has not made enough 
necessary reforms to cut the wasteful, cozy ties between too many 
bankers and business leaders that are holding back growth 
prospects. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the economy will bounce back,'' said Hitomi  
Hayashi, 38, a housewife who was shopping in Tokyo's busy Ginza 
district. ``My husband's salary has been cut little by little for 
some time, so I buy things in bargain sales. I am worried about the 
future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hideyoshi Hagimoto, 25, thinks Japan will bounce back because  
sales at the ad agency where he works bottomed out in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it is true my bonus was cut,'' he said. ``I don't think  
things will ever get as good as they used to be, but I think they 
can be a little better than how they are now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The credit rating agency Moody's Investors Service recently  
noted positive changes in Japan's business culture, with some 
companies focusing on profits and cutting out wasteful spending 
rather than depending on limitless loans from friendly bankers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The big issue now is Japanese banks for the first time ... are  
asking companies, `Are you profitable?''' said Masaharu Kakutani, 
representative director of Moody's Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, once a booming success story, the economy has been  
shrinking in its worst recession in years. Unemployment hit a 
record 5.8 percent, with many people who keep their jobs still 
seeing their pay cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Filipino women who work as maids in Hong Kong recently saw the  
government slash their minimum salary by 5 percent, to the 
equivalent of $470 a month. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are the lowest paid workers in Hong Kong. And we have the  
meanest job,'' said Rosa Pimental, 41, who works six days a week to 
support her husband and two sons back in the Philippines. ``I would 
go home at once if I had a permanent job, but there's nothing back 
home and I have to stay here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's response: Lots of other people are getting their  
wages cut or losing jobs in a recession that shows no immediate 
signs of ending, so the maids should get less, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, instability persists in Indonesia, where the crisis  
abruptly ended the 32-year-reign of President Suharto. Indonesia's 
economy is still shrinking, although analysts don't expect the 
devastating 14 percent decline of last year. It was forced to get a 
$43 billion rescue package from the IMF. 
</P>
<P>
	The government puts Indonesian unemployment at 22 percent,  
though some outside experts say that may be exaggerated. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysia is a bit of a wild card. The government predicts 1  
percent growth in its economy, although private economists have 
estimates ranging from a 3 percent gain to a 3 percent contraction. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore's economy ended 1998 in recession, and due to the  
problems in neighboring Indonesia and Malaysia, Singaporean 
officials have said 1999 could be even worse. 
</P>
<P>
	The economies of Taiwan and China, which so far have escaped  
recession, are likely to see slower growth this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In Thailand, where the crisis began with the devaluation of the  
baht currency, experts predict an end to the sharp economic 
contraction. The economy, which shrank nearly 8 percent last year, 
could grow slightly this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
