<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Temple Coach Sets Wins Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Leave it to John Chaney to protest the game  
that made him the winningest coach in Temple history. 
</P>
<P>
	And excuse the 67-year-old coach for changing his mind when  
victory No. 374 was in the books. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll change it now,'' Chaney said after passing Harry Litwack  
for No. 1 on the Owls' victory list with a 72-56 win over George 
Washington on Saturday. ``What would I look like out in the middle 
of the ocean and throwing the paddles out of the boat? That's 
stupid, isn't it?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chaney, in his 17th season at Temple, got his 599th career  
victory and 374th for the Owls in a game that had all the elements 
that have come to define him. He chastised his team, belittled and 
intimidated the refs and, yes, announced that he was protesting the 
game because he disagreed with the officiating. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as he accepted the game ball and made a moving tribute to  
the 91-year-old Litwack at center court, Chaney couldn't pass up 
the chance for a punchline. 
</P>
<P>
	``He set a record that should never be broken,'' Chaney said to  
a standing ovation. ``He's a great man, and I feel bad because this 
is the worst team I've ever coached in my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chaney is 374-157 (.704) since taking over the Owls program in  
1982 and goes for his 600th career victory at home Wednesday night 
against Fordham. 
</P>
<P>
	Litwack, a cigar-smoking gentleman known as ``The Chief,'' was  
373-193 (.659) from 1952-73. After the game, Chaney got a call from 
the man he surpassed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish I could be there with you,'' Chaney told Litwack, who  
lives in Miami Beach. ``I'll come visit you. I love you very much. 
I wish I could have played for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chaney seemed determined to coach this game as if he were in the  
Final Four -- the one goal he has failed to attain at Temple (18-8, 
12-2 Atlantic 10). 
</P>
<P>
	Chaney jumped out of his seat to yank freshman Ron Rollerson  
after a brief stint in the opening minutes, screaming, ``Get him 
out of there!'' He slammed his clipboard on the court during a 
timeout in the second half -- after the Owls had seized their 
second-biggest lead of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got kids who come from different backgrounds,'' Chaney  
said. ``And many times, most of the backgrounds are losing 
backgrounds -- all negative. Everybody knows, everybody has the will 
to win. Very few people know how to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After flirting with technicals in arguments with referee Reggie  
Greenwood, Chaney motioned for official Tom Clark to join him for a 
discussion. ``Come here!'' the coach screamed, and Clark jogged 
over for his tongue-lashing. When he was finished, Chaney ripped 
his sports coat off and rolled up his sleeves. 
</P>
<P>
	``A game like this, this late in the season, and they give me  
these refs,'' Chaney lamented early in the game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
