<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rodman's Decision May Come Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- After all the waiting and all the  
guessing, Dennis Rodman may finally say Monday whether he's going 
Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, there's no telling what he might talk about.  
</P>
<P>
	The seven-time NBA rebounding champion has called a news  
conference at Planet Hollywood, and might announce whether he 
intends to play for the Los Angeles Lakers this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman had been expected to join the Lakers ever since a  
newspaper report Feb. 13 that quoted sources close to Rodman as 
saying he had decided to play for the Lakers. A source close to the 
Lakers told The Associated Press on Feb. 14 the team expected to 
have him signed within a couple days. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then Rodman, who turns 38 in May, has offered conflicting  
comments about his plans. He told a Chicago Sun-Times reporter 
Wednesday he would sign with the team by the end of the week and 
even met with Lakers owner Jerry Buss that night. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days later, Rodman said on ESPN's ``Up Close'' he hadn't  
come to a decision and would make an announcement after using the 
weekend to ``put my mind at ease and at peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman has apparently been annoyed because he can't earn more  
money under the NBA's new labor agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers, who are over the salary cap, can sign him only for  
the veterans' minimum of $1 million, pro-rated to $600,000 for the 
shortened season and now under $500,000 because of the 10 games the 
team has already played. 
</P>
<P>
	However, one of the terms of Rodman's contract with Converse is  
that he receives $3 million if he plays in Los Angeles, Chicago or 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman made clear his resentment concerning the NBA's new labor  
agreement on ``Up Close.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It ain't about Dennis Rodman trying to be greedy, it's not  
about that,'' he said. ``They've put me in a bind where I can't do 
anything but make the minimum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, former Lakers great Magic Johnson, now a part-owner  
and vice president of the team, said on David Letterman's ``The 
Late Show'' Thursday night he was tired of the distraction Rodman 
was causing and he would ``love us just to say forget it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Rodman joins the Lakers, he could make his debut with the  
team Thursday, when the Lakers face the Los Angeles Clippers at the 
Anaheim Arena, or the following night when the same teams meet at 
the Forum in Inglewood. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers are currently out of town, playing at Denver on  
Monday night and Vancouver on Tuesday night before returning home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
