<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N. Carolina, Virginia Play Classic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Calling it a mismatch appeared to be  
an understatement with No. 14 North Carolina facing undermanned, 
under-the-weather Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	But it wound up as one of the most exciting games of the college  
basketball season, with Ademola Okulaja hitting a 3-pointer with 
1.4 seconds left to give the Tar Heels a 67-66 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``They worked hard,'' Okulaja said after rescuing his team from  
the upset. ``They punished us for every mistake we made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After falling behind 15-0 and missing their first 10 shots, the  
Cavaliers, who have only six scholarship players, came back. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia even took the lead before halftime and stayed with the  
Tar Heels throughout the second half, leading seven different times 
and never allowing their hated rivals to go ahead by more than 4 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Okulaja connected on a 3-pointer and Ed Cota made a basket,  
giving North Carolina a 64-62 lead, but a 3-pointer by Cavaliers 
freshman Adam Hall with 49 seconds left enabled Virginia to regain 
the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Chezley Watson converted only one of two free throws, making it  
66-64 with 14.3 seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came the play that kept Cavaliers fans from rushing onto  
the court. 
</P>
<P>
	Cota penetrated into the lane and found a wide-open Okulaja, who  
nailed the game-winner -- which may have ended Virginia's postseason 
hopes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This meant a lot to us and to the alumni,'' Watson said.  
``We're still searching for one more win to get us into the NIT and 
it just slipped right out of our hands. When it happens like that, 
it's tough to swallow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the Tar Heels' victory, Ronald Curry's return to  
Virginia was far from memorable. 
</P>
<P>
	The Virginia high school phenom scored only 3 points in 19  
minutes. Curry verbally committed to Virginia before changing his 
mind and heading to North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Signs like ``Benedict Curry,'' ``I Hate Curry,'' and one  
comparing his numbers to those of Cavaliers walk-on Josh Hare 
served to ``welcome'' Curry home. 
</P>
<P>
	``They love me here, don't they?'' Curry quipped after being  
jeered each time he touched the ball. 
</P>
</TEXT>
