<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strauss' ``Elektra'' Revived at Met </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Louder!'' composer Richard Strauss is said to  
have shouted to the conductor of the 115-piece orchestra during 
rehearsals for the world premiere of ``Elektra'' in 1909. ``I can 
still hear the voice of Frau Heink.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Contralto Ernestine Schumann-Heink, in the role of Klytemnestra,  
was not amused and returned the compliment by describing the music 
as ``a dreadful racket.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ninety years later, Strauss' one-act masterpiece still tests the  
ability of orchestra and singers alike -- not just to make 
themselves heard, but to bring out the beauty and grandeur in a 
score that with its raucous dissonance often seems to stretch 
tonality to its limits. 
</P>
<P>
	The Metropolitan Opera's revival Friday night met most of  
``Elektra's'' challenges extremely well. The orchestra, conducted 
by James Levine, played with hair-raising intensity and splendor. 
And much of the singing was first-rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Where the performance fell short was where it usually does -- in  
the casting of the title role, which demands a dramatic soprano 
with lungs of steel who can declaim at full throttle for two hours 
with scarcely a rest. 
</P>
<P>
	As the daughter of Agamemnon, obsessed with avenging his murder  
at the hands of her mother, Gabriele Schnaut sang with energy and 
plenty of volume, but her voice lacked security in the crucial 
upper register. Any note above the staff -- and there are many, 
including a couple of high Cs -- tended to come out harsh or 
off-pitch. Her few quiet moments, such as the beautiful Recognition 
Scene with her brother, Orest, were more effective. 
</P>
<P>
	To Schnaut's credit, her performance was carefully thought out  
and at times compelling, within the confines of the garish Otto 
Schenk production. At the end, the audience cheered her for sheer 
survival in what may be the most punishing role in the repertory. 
</P>
<P>
	Listening to her scenes with her sister, Chrysothemis, one  
wondered what it would be like to hear Deborah Voigt in the title 
role. Her soft-grained soprano showed startling power and freedom 
in the climaxes, enveloping her high notes with a creamy tone and 
no trace of strain. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the casting was exemplary: Mezzo Hanna Schwarz sang  
and acted vividly as their mother, Klytemnestra; baritone Monte 
Pederson made an impressive debut as an Orest of warmth and 
nobility, and veteran tenor Kenneth Riegel did well in his brief 
scene as Aegisth, Klytemnestra's paramour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
