<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewis Says No to Drugs, Yes to Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Juliette Lewis is back making movies after a  
break to kick her drug habit. 
</P>
<P>
	The rising star of the late '80s and early '90s, who received an  
Academy Award nomination for ``Cape Fear,'' dropped out of sight in 
1996 after playing Shirley MacLaine's granddaughter in ``The 
Evening Star.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She moved to Florida to live with her mother and enter a  
rehabilition program run by the Church of Scientology. She admits 
that by then things had gotten out of hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bravest thing I ever did was continuing to live when I  
wanted to die,'' Lewis says in Sunday's Daily News. ``That's all 
melodramatic, but it's not melodramatic. Actually, I lived it, but 
that moment in time. But continuing past that point and having some 
kind of faith that I could be strong and love life again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis' new film is ``The Other Sister,'' in which she plays a  
mentally retarded woman trying to achieve some independence and 
pursue a romance. After that, she'll appear with William Hurt in 
the thriller ``The 4th Floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Past credits include ``Kalifornia,'' ``What's Eating Gilbert  
Grape?,'' ``Strange Days'' and ``Natural Born Killers.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
