<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Attendant Talks Disrupted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- A group of Northwest Airlines flight  
attendants hope hand-delivered petitions with more than 8,000 
signatures will have an impact on negotiators hammering out a new 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine flight attendants tried to barge in on negotiations in  
downtown Minneapolis Saturday and deliver the petitions, which said 
the attendants will ``fight for a fair contract.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The flight attendants were stymied when federal mediator  
Laurette Piculin initially refused to let them into the room, said 
Billie Davenport, chairwoman of the flight attendants' negotiating 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Davenport, the highest elected officer of Teamsters Local 2000,  
said the surprise visit rankled Northwest's bargaining team because 
the protesters had invited the news media. 
</P>
<P>
	Piculin opened the door and quickly shut it. But about 10  
minutes later Davenport led her negotiating team into the hall to 
accept the petitions. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the group said they were disappointed because they  
wanted to confront the company's negotiators. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to strike, but we will if we have to,'' flight  
attendant Amy Morton of San Francisco told Davenport. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest spokesman Jon Austin said the company is optimistic  
that an agreement will be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Davenport said she hopes a settlement can be reached by the end  
of March. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
