<DOCNO> APW19990221.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-21 19:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Red Sox Lefties Eager To Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Two lefty relievers are eager to return  
to Fenway Park, hoping to help the Red Sox win. That's about where 
the similarities end. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Guthrie, expected to be the top lefty in the bullpen, grew  
up in the Boston area and spent several birthdays watching the Red 
Sox in person. 
</P>
<P>
	Rheal Cormier, a longshot for a job, grew up in Canada, spent  
1995 with Boston but pitched only one major league game the past 
two years because of arm troubles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a nice situation to be in as a left-handed reliever  
because of their scarcity,'' Guthrie said Sunday, the first workout 
day for pitchers and catchers, ``but you still have to go out and 
produce.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guthrie signed as a free agent after spending the last 3 1/2  
seasons with Los Angeles. He spent his other 6 1/2 years with 
Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Cormier was 7-5 with Boston in 1995 in 48 games, 12 of them  
starts, then was traded to Montreal. He was 7-10 the next year then 
pitched one game in 1997 before undergoing tendon transplant 
surgery in his left elbow that ended his season. He signed with 
Cleveland before the 1998 season but pitched just 9 2-3 innings for 
Double-A Akron before a sore shoulder ended his season. Boston 
signed him as a free agent last Jan. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Cormier said his arm feels strong but there appears to be only  
one open spot on Boston's projected 11-man pitching staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now I just want my arm to feel good and be able to take  
the ball and go out there when they ask me to go,'' he said. ``I'm 
just going out there knowing I don't have any pains.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he chose Boston over other interested teams because he  
enjoyed his season with the Red Sox and had worked with Boston 
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan when both were in Montreal in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``He basically knows all my mechanics,'' Cormier said. ``If I  
would do something wrong early, he'd be able to correct me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cormier, 31, figures to start the season at Triple A-Pawtucket  
since Boston has 29 pitchers in the major league camp and only 
plans to keep 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Guthrie, 33, figures to spend the season as Boston's primary  
lefty reliever. In his time with Los Angeles, he had a 3.67 ERA and 
5-10 record in 216 innings over 205 games. He can serve as a setup 
man for Tom Gordon, who converted 46 of 47 save opportunities last 
season, his first as a closer. 
</P>
<P>
	``My job is to help to get him on the mound and put him in that  
situation again,'' Guthrie said. 
</P>
<P>
	Guthrie attended elementary school in Scituate, a suburb south  
of Boston, before moving to Venice, Fla., where he didn't even make 
his high school team. But he won a spot as a walk-on at Louisiana 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	He was glad when the Red Sox called.  
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't really want to be on the West Coast because we live  
in Florida, so it's an easy trip for us'' to Boston, Guthrie said. 
``We're familiar with the area and I have a lot of memories through 
my youth of baseball at Fenway Park.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They always had good teams and it was always a special feeling  
going back there to play them when I was with Minnesota,'' he 
added, ``so it was an exciting opportunity for me to get a chance 
to come here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cormier feels the same way, even though there's no guarantee  
he'll stay in the majors. At least he's pitching without pain 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	``When a ballplayer has major surgery, almost career-ending,  
you're always thinking, `Am I ever going to be the same?' '' 
Cormier said. ``I feel good right now. I feel my arm is really 
coming back where it was before.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
