<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Feb. 21, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	NATO Plan Stalls Kosovo Peace Deal  
</P>
<P>
	RAMBOUILLET, France (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine  
Albright, making scant headway toward a Kosovo peace settlement, 
said Sunday that if neither Serbs nor ethnic Albanians accept the 
six-nation plan, NATO cannot carry through on its threat to attack 
Serb targets. With a new deadline set for Tuesday, Serb negotiators 
``are not engaging at all'' over the critical question of whether 
NATO peacekeepers would enforce the settlement, while the Kosovar 
Albanians must still be persuaded to sign on fully with the plan to 
give them greater autonomy in the Serb province, Albright said. 

</P>
<P>
	US, British Jets Attack Iraqi Sites  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- U.S. and British warplanes attacked an  
Iraqi missile base and two military communication sites Sunday 
after Iraqi jets violated the no-fly zone, the U.S. military said. 
There was no immediate word on damage or casualties from the 
strikes near al-Amarah and Tallil, about 170 miles southeast of 
Baghdad. All the planes returned to their base, a statement from 
the U.S. Central Command said. There was no immediate comment from 
Iraqi officials on the attack. 

</P>
<P>
	Bogota Blast Injures Eight  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A bomb exploded in a crowded capital  
street Sunday and injured eight passersby, two seriously, police 
said. The 11-pound dynamite explosive also buckled doors and 
shattered windows of nearby buildings and left a crater three feet 
in diameter and nearly two feet deep. It wasn't immediately clear 
what the bomb was contained in. Police said they were investigating 
and there had been no claims of responsibility for the blast. 

</P>
<P>
	States Target Sweepstakes Gimmicks  
</P>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Frustrated with consumer complaints and  
filing costly lawsuits against mail-in sweepstakes, attorneys 
general from nine states and representatives from 16 others are 
meeting to discuss ways to halt deceptive gimmicks. Indiana has 
lawsuits pending against American Family Publishers and Publishers 
Clearing House, two of the giants in the industry, claiming they 
use deceptive mailings to trick people into purchasing magazines 
and other products in hopes it will help them win. Other attorneys 
general planning to attend are from Oklahoma, Florida, Mississippi, 
Missouri, New Mexico, Ohio, Pennsylvania and Wisconsin. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspects in Ireland Attack Arrested  
</P>
<P>
	DUNDALK, Ireland (AP) -- Police on both sides of the Irish border  
arrested seven men Sunday in last year's car bombing in Omagh, the 
deadliest terrorist strike in Northern Ireland's 30-year conflict. 
In the Irish Republic, five men were questioned under Ireland's 
Offenses Against the State Act anti-terrorist laws. Detectives in 
Northern Ireland, ruled by the British, arrested two men. Police 
have so far arrested more than 60 suspects in both Northern Ireland 
and the Irish Republic, but no one has been charged in connection 
with the Aug. 15 car bombing that killed 29 people and wounded 370. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Probes Congo Human Rights  
</P>
<P>
	GOMA, Congo (AP) -- A U.N. human rights investigator held talks  
with Congolese rebels Sunday as part of a new investigation into 
allegations that both the government and rebels were abusing human 
rights. Roberto Garreton, a Chilean lawyer, said questions about 
Congo's human rights record led to the new inquiry. The rebels have 
been accused of massacring hundreds of civilians in eastern Congo, 
where the war-weary population has shown little faith in the 
six-month-old insurgency against President Laurent Kabila and often 
cooperates with tribal militiamen fighting what they say is a Tutsi 
domination. 

</P>
<P>
	Italy Telecom To Fight Takeover Bid  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Telecom Italia plans to challenge Olivetti's bold  
$58 billion takeover bid, which, if pulled off by a relative David 
of the telecommunications industry, would be one of Europe's 
biggest deals ever. Both Telecom Italia SpA and Telecom Italia 
Mobile, Europe's biggest mobile phone operator which is largely 
owned by Telecom Italia, held board meetings this weekend to 
discuss the bid, as did Olivetti SpA. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Up in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices advanced moderately Monday. The  
Nikkei rose 52.13 points to 14,150.17 in the first 30 minutes of 
trading. 

</P>
<P>
	SuperSonics Top Lakers 92-89  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Gary Payton scored 26 points and Olden Polynice  
had 15 points and a season-high 17 rebounds Sunday to lead the 
Seattle SuperSonics to a 92-89 victory over the Los Angeles Lakers. 
The Sonics bounced back after a 30-point loss in Utah Saturday and 
beat a Lakers team that eliminated them from the NBA playoffs last 
season, costing coach George Karl his job. The Lakers got 27 points 
and 10 rebounds from Shaquille O'Neal, while Kobe Bryant added 23 
points and 13 rebounds. Vin Baker had a season-high 19 points, 
while Detlef Schrempf had 15 points for Seattle. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by STEPHANIE GASKELL  

</P>
</TEXT>
