<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Shakespeare In Love' Wins Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The authors of the romantic comedy  
``Shakespeare In Love'' beat the writers of the harrowing war drama 
``Saving Private Ryan'' to win the Writers Guild of America award 
for original screenplay. 
</P>
<P>
	Marc Norman and Tom Stoppard shared the award for  
``Shakespeare,'' which bested ``Bulworth,'' with screenplay by 
Warren Beatty and Jeremy Pikser; ``Saving Private Ryan,'' by Robert 
Rodat; ``The Truman Show,'' by Andrew Niccol; and ``The Opposite of 
Sex,'' by Don Roos. 
</P>
<P>
	``Out of Sight'' was the guild's pick for best screenplay based  
on material previously produced or published. The screenplay, 
written by Scott Frank, was based on a novel by Elmore Leonard. 
</P>
<P>
	Other contenders for this award were ``A Civil Action,'' by  
Steven Zaillian, based on the book by Jonathan Harr; ``Gods and 
Monsters,'' by Bill Condon, based on the novel by Christopher Bram; 
``Primary Colors,'' by Elaine May, based on the novel by Anonymous; 
and ``A Simple Plan,'' by Scott B. Smith, based on his novel. 
</P>
<P>
	The guild's 51st annual awards were announced Saturday in  
ceremonies held in Beverly Hills and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The awards are considered an indication of where Oscar awards  
for screenwriting might go on March 23. Norman and Stoppard won the 
Golden Globe screenwriting award last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Other guild awards announced Saturday:  
</P>
<P>
	TELEVISION:   	
</P>
<P>
	ORIGINAL LONG FORM -- ``Labor of Love,'' Nina Shengold, Lifetime.  
</P>
<P>
	ADAPTED LONG FORM -- ``The Love Letter,'' James Henerson, based  
on the short story by Jack Finney, CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	EPISODIC DRAMA -- ``Proofs for the Existence of God (Nothing  
Sacred),'' Bill Cain (aka Paul Leland), ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	EPISODIC COMEDY -- ``Frasier's Imaginary Friend (Frasier),'' Rob  
Greenberg, NBC. 
</P>
<P>
	COMEDY/VARIETY -- MUSIC, AWARDS, TRIBUTES, SPECIALS (ANY LENGTH)  
-- ``Ellen: A Hollywood Tribute,'' Tim Doyle, ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	COMEDY/VARIETY (INCLUDING TALK) SERIES -- ``Dennis Miller Live,''  
Eddie Feldmann, David Feldman, Jose Arroyo, Leah Krinsky, Dennis 
Miller, Jim Hanna, David Weiss, HBO. 
</P>
<P>
	DAYTIME SERIALS -- ``All My Children,'' Agnes Nixon, Megan  
McTavish, Lorraine Broderick, Hal Corley, Frederick Johnson, Peggy 
Sloans, Victor Miller, Craig Carlson, N. Gail Lawrence, Juliet Law 
Packer, Karen Lewis, Michelle Patrick, Bettina F. Bradbury, Judith 
Donato, Kathleen Klein, Caroline Franz, Charlotte Gibson, Elizabeth 
Page, Sharon Epstein, ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	CHILDREN'S SCRIPT --''Telly As Jack (Sesame Street),'' Christine  
Ferraro, PBS. 
</P>
<P>
	DOCUMENTARY CURRENT EVENTS --''Once Upon A Time in Arkansas,''  
Michael Kirk, Peter J. Boyer, PBS. 
</P>
<P>
	DOCUMENTARY OTHER THAN CURRENT EVENTS -- ``Truman (The American  
Experience),'' David Grubin, PBS. 
</P>
<P>
	NEWS -- REGULARLY SCHEDULED, BULLETIN OR BREAKING REPORT --  
``Farewell To A Princess,'' Jerry Cipriano, L. Franklin DeVine, 
CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	NEWS -- ANALYSIS, FEATURE OR COMMENTARY -- ``Theodore Kaczynski's  
Brother (Good Morning America),'' Edmund Levin, ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	RADIO:   	
</P>
<P>
	DOCUMENTARY -- ``The Nature of Giving,'' Ruth Davis, ABC Radio  
Network. 
</P>
<P>
	NEWS -- REGULARLY SCHEDULED, BULLETIN OR BREAKING REPORT --  
``World News This Week,'' Stuart J. Chamberlain, Jr., ABC Radio 
Network. 
</P>
<P>
	NEWS -- ANALYSIS, FEATURE OR COMMENTARY -- (Three way tie)  
``Goodnight Moon,'' Andrea Smith Stapleton, ABC Radio Network; 
``Sinatra (Dan Rather Reporting),'' Greg Kandra, CBS Radio Network; 
``Frank Sinatra: The Final Curtain,'' Hank Weinbloom, ABC Radio 
Network. 
</P>
<P>
	ON AIR PROMOTION -- CBS Promotions, Nancy McColgan, CBS.  
</P>
<P>
	GRAPHIC ANIMATION -- CBS Graphic Animation, designed by Beth  
Leudesdorf, CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	GRAPHIC DESIGN FOR PACKAGE/CAMPAIGN/SERIES -- ``60 Minutes at  
30,'' designed by Beth Leudesdorf, CBS. 
</P>
